window.CISSP = window.CISSP || {}; CISSP.reading = CISSP.reading || {};
CISSP.reading[5] = [];
CISSP.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Physical & Logical Access Control to Assets", body:"<p>Domain 5 opens with the deceptively simple objective of controlling <span class='keyterm'>physical and logical access to assets</span> - information, systems, devices, facilities, applications, and services. For a CISSP the framing is not \"which switch do I flip\" but \"which assets are worth protecting, who is accountable for the access decision, and how do controls at different layers combine into defense in depth.\" Access control is the operational expression of the CIA triad: it preserves <span class='keyterm'>confidentiality</span> by keeping the unauthorized out, protects <span class='keyterm'>integrity</span> by limiting who may alter data, and can even support <span class='keyterm'>availability</span> by preventing resource exhaustion. Every control you place is ultimately a business decision an asset owner makes to reduce risk to an acceptable level.</p><h3>Subjects, objects, and the reference monitor</h3><p>Access control theory rests on a small vocabulary you must own cold. A <span class='keyterm'>subject</span> is the active entity requesting access - a user, process, or device acting on someone's behalf. An <span class='keyterm'>object</span> is the passive resource being acted upon - a file, table, room, or service. Between them sits the <span class='keyterm'>reference monitor</span>, the abstract concept that mediates every access attempt and enforces the security policy. Its concrete implementation is the <span class='keyterm'>security kernel</span>, which must be tamperproof, always invoked (non-bypassable), and small enough to be verifiable. When a scenario describes access decisions being made \"in one place, for every request, that cannot be circumvented,\" it is invoking the reference-monitor concept - a favorite exam anchor.</p><h3>Physical versus logical controls</h3><p>Access controls are conventionally split by the plane on which they operate. <span class='keyterm'>Physical controls</span> govern access to tangible assets and the spaces that house them: fences, bollards, mantraps, locks, badge readers, guards, and CCTV. <span class='keyterm'>Logical (technical) controls</span> govern access to electronic assets: authentication systems, permissions, ACLs, encryption, and firewalls. A third category, <span class='keyterm'>administrative (managerial) controls</span>, sets the policy the other two enforce - hiring practices, security awareness training, and access-review procedures. The professional insight is that these layers are complementary, not substitutes: full-disk encryption (logical) does nothing against a shoulder-surfer, and a locked door (physical) does nothing against a stolen credential used remotely.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Control plane</th><th>Protects</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Physical</td><td>Facilities, devices, media</td><td>Mantraps, badge readers, guards, locks, CCTV</td></tr><tr><td>Logical / technical</td><td>Systems, applications, data</td><td>Authentication, ACLs, encryption, MFA</td></tr><tr><td>Administrative</td><td>People and process</td><td>Policy, training, background checks, access reviews</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Control functions: the classic taxonomy</h3><p>CISSP also classifies controls by <em>function</em> - what the control does in time relative to an incident. Mastering this taxonomy lets you answer the ubiquitous \"which type of control is this\" question instantly.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Physical example</th><th>Logical example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Directive</td><td>Mandate behavior</td><td>\"Authorized personnel only\" sign</td><td>Acceptable use policy banner</td></tr><tr><td>Deterrent</td><td>Discourage the attempt</td><td>Visible guard, fence</td><td>Warning banner, logging notice</td></tr><tr><td>Preventive</td><td>Stop the act</td><td>Locked door, mantrap</td><td>Firewall, access permission</td></tr><tr><td>Detective</td><td>Identify the act</td><td>CCTV, motion sensor</td><td>IDS, audit log review</td></tr><tr><td>Corrective</td><td>Fix after the fact</td><td>Fire suppression</td><td>Quarantine, patch</td></tr><tr><td>Recovery</td><td>Restore operation</td><td>Rebuild facility</td><td>Restore from backup</td></tr><tr><td>Compensating</td><td>Alternative when primary is infeasible</td><td>Guard where no lock fits</td><td>Extra monitoring for a legacy system</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>A single mechanism can serve multiple functions depending on framing. A fence is <strong>deterrent</strong> when it discourages and <strong>preventive</strong> when it physically blocks. A CCTV camera is <strong>deterrent</strong> if visible and <strong>detective</strong> when its footage is reviewed. Read the scenario for the <em>intended effect</em>, and remember a <strong>compensating</strong> control is the answer whenever the primary control cannot be implemented but the risk must still be treated.</p></div><h3>Assets are more than servers</h3><p>Objective 5.1 deliberately enumerates a broad asset list - information, systems, devices, facilities, applications, and services - to force you past a narrow server-centric view. A modern access-control program must reach identities in a SaaS <span class='keyterm'>service</span>, API keys for an <span class='keyterm'>application</span>, mobile <span class='keyterm'>devices</span> under a BYOD policy, and the badge-access to a data-center <span class='keyterm'>facility</span>, all governed under one coherent policy set. The asset owner - a business role, not IT - determines the sensitivity of the asset and therefore the strength of control it warrants, applying the classification scheme from Domain 2. IT acts as custodian, implementing what the owner decides.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A firm encrypts every laptop and mandates MFA on its VPN, yet an intruder tailgates through an unlocked loading dock, walks into an unattended office, and photographs a whiteboard covered in unreleased financials. Strong logical controls did nothing because the exposure was physical. The CISSP lesson: controls must be balanced across planes, and the whiteboard - <em>information</em>, an asset in its own right - needed a clean-desk directive and physical access control, not another logical layer.</p></div><h3>Defense in depth and the value of layering</h3><p>The organizing principle behind all of this is <span class='keyterm'>defense in depth</span> - layering controls so that the failure of any single one does not result in compromise. A remote attacker seeking a database record might have to defeat perimeter filtering, network segmentation, host authentication, application authorization, and record-level encryption in turn. Each layer buys detection time and raises attacker cost. The complementary idea is that controls should map to a documented risk: over-controlling a low-value public asset wastes budget, while under-controlling a crown-jewel asset invites catastrophe. This is why access-control design begins with asset valuation and classification, not with a product purchase - the technology is the last decision, downstream of the governance ones about what the asset is worth and who owns the risk.</p><h3>Control categories versus control types: two orthogonal axes</h3><p>Candidates routinely conflate two distinct classification schemes, and the exam exploits the confusion. The first axis is the <em>category</em> - the plane on which a control operates: <span class='keyterm'>administrative</span>, <span class='keyterm'>technical (logical)</span>, or <span class='keyterm'>physical</span>. The second axis is the <em>function</em> - what the control does in time relative to an event: directive, deterrent, preventive, detective, corrective, recovery, or compensating. These axes are orthogonal, meaning any control can be plotted as a coordinate pair. A security-awareness program is <em>administrative</em> in category and <em>preventive</em> in function. A CCTV camera is <em>physical</em> in category and either <em>deterrent</em> or <em>detective</em> in function depending on framing. An intrusion-detection system is <em>technical</em> and <em>detective</em>. When a question asks you to classify a control, first decide which axis it is testing - category or function - because the same mechanism yields different correct answers on each axis, and mixing them produces a wrong response even when your reasoning about the mechanism is sound.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Control example</th><th>Category axis</th><th>Function axis</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Security-awareness training</td><td>Administrative</td><td>Preventive</td></tr><tr><td>Firewall rule</td><td>Technical</td><td>Preventive</td></tr><tr><td>Locked server-room door</td><td>Physical</td><td>Preventive</td></tr><tr><td>Reviewed CCTV footage</td><td>Physical</td><td>Detective</td></tr><tr><td>Backup restore</td><td>Technical</td><td>Recovery</td></tr><tr><td>Guard posted where no lock fits</td><td>Physical</td><td>Compensating</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Worked example: layering controls on one asset</h3><p>Consider a single high-value asset - the payroll database - and trace how a CISSP layers every category and function against it. <em>Administrative directive:</em> a data-classification policy labels payroll as confidential and names the CFO as asset owner. <em>Administrative preventive:</em> background checks screen anyone granted access, and separation of duties splits the person who edits salaries from the person who approves the pay run. <em>Physical preventive:</em> the database servers sit in a locked, badge-controlled data center behind a mantrap. <em>Technical preventive:</em> role-based permissions, network segmentation, and transparent data encryption restrict and protect the records. <em>Technical detective:</em> database activity monitoring and a SIEM alert on bulk reads. <em>Physical detective:</em> reviewed door logs and CCTV establish who entered the facility. <em>Corrective and recovery:</em> automated backups plus a tested restore procedure return the data after corruption. <em>Compensating:</em> where a legacy reporting tool cannot support MFA, extra monitoring and a jump host stand in for the missing control. The single asset now enjoys defense in depth across every plane and every function - the picture the CISSP is expected to be able to construct on demand.</p><h3>Least privilege and need-to-know as design defaults</h3><p>Underneath every access decision sit two disciplines the CISSP treats as non-negotiable defaults. <span class='keyterm'>Least privilege</span> holds that a subject should receive only the minimum access required to perform its function and no more, so that a compromised account or a mistaken action can reach only a small blast radius. <span class='keyterm'>Need-to-know</span> is the confidentiality-focused sibling: even a subject with the right clearance level should only reach the specific information its current task requires, not the entire pool at that level. The two combine with <span class='keyterm'>separation of duties</span> to bound both the reach and the concentration of any single identity's power. A closely related default is <span class='keyterm'>implicit deny</span> - the principle that anything not expressly permitted is refused, so that gaps in policy fail closed rather than open. When a scenario describes access granted \"just in case it might be needed,\" or a permission that outlives the task that justified it, the violated principle is least privilege, and the corrective is to strip the access back to the demonstrable minimum and let policy default to deny.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An auditor asks a security manager to categorize the organization's badge-access system. The manager answers \"preventive\" and is marked wrong - the auditor wanted the <em>category</em> (physical), not the function. The lesson mirrors the exam trap exactly: badge access is <strong>physical</strong> on the category axis and <strong>preventive</strong> on the function axis, and both are correct depending on which axis the question tests. Always confirm whether the stem asks <em>what plane</em> the control operates on or <em>what it does in time</em> before selecting an answer.</p></div><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>A frequent error is treating physical and logical controls as interchangeable trade-offs when they defend different attack surfaces and must both be present for sensitive assets. Another is conflating the reference monitor (the concept) with the security kernel (its implementation) - the exam distinguishes them. A third is assuming \"preventive is always best\"; in reality detective and corrective controls are indispensable because prevention inevitably fails, and a mature program assumes breach and instruments accordingly. Finally, remember that access control is a lifecycle, not a one-time grant: without periodic review, permissions decay into privilege creep and the elegant model on paper drifts far from the messy reality in production.</p>"},
  {heading:"Identification, Authentication & AAA", body:"<p>Before any access decision can be made, four distinct things must happen in order, and the CISSP exam relentlessly tests whether you can keep them separate. <span class='keyterm'>Identification</span> is the claim of who you are; <span class='keyterm'>authentication</span> is the proof of that claim; <span class='keyterm'>authorization</span> is the decision about what the proven identity may do; and <span class='keyterm'>accountability</span> is the traceable record of what they did. Collapse any two of these in your mind and a whole class of exam questions becomes a coin flip. This section builds the mental model that anchors the rest of the domain.</p><h3>The four stages, in strict order</h3><p>Think of entering a secure building. You state your name and show an employee number - that is <span class='keyterm'>identification</span>, an assertion that carries no proof. You place your finger on a reader that matches you to that number - that is <span class='keyterm'>authentication</span>, the binding of the claim to evidence. The system checks whether that verified identity is permitted into the server room - that is <span class='keyterm'>authorization</span>. Finally, the badge log records the entry with a timestamp - that supports <span class='keyterm'>accountability</span>. Identification must be <em>unique</em> (no shared accounts) or accountability collapses, because you can no longer trace an action to one human. Authentication must be <em>secret or hard to forge</em>, or the proof is worthless.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Question answered</th><th>Example</th><th>Failure if missing</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Identification</td><td>Who do you claim to be?</td><td>Username, employee ID</td><td>No basis for any decision</td></tr><tr><td>Authentication</td><td>Can you prove it?</td><td>Password + token</td><td>Anyone can impersonate</td></tr><tr><td>Authorization</td><td>What may you do?</td><td>Permission check against policy</td><td>Verified users over-reach</td></tr><tr><td>Accountability</td><td>What did you do?</td><td>Audit log entry</td><td>No traceability or non-repudiation</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The AAA model and its two expansions</h3><p>Industry compresses these ideas into <span class='keyterm'>AAA</span>, but be careful - the acronym expands two ways. In the network-access world (RADIUS, TACACS+, Diameter), AAA is <span class='keyterm'>Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting</span>, where accounting means metering session usage for billing and audit. In the broader security-governance world, the third A is often rendered as <span class='keyterm'>Accountability</span>, the property that actions can be traced to a responsible identity. Both readings are legitimate; the exam expects you to recognize accounting as the network-protocol term and accountability as the governance property they enable. Identification and authentication together are the first A; authorization is the second; logging/accounting is the third.</p><h3>Accountability, non-repudiation, and the audit trail</h3><p>Accountability is only real if three preconditions hold: unique identification, reliable authentication, and a protected <span class='keyterm'>audit trail</span>. Shared or generic accounts (a single \"admin\" login used by five people) destroy accountability because no action maps to one person. Strong accountability yields <span class='keyterm'>non-repudiation</span> - the assurance that an actor cannot credibly deny having performed an action, typically reinforced by digital signatures and tamper-evident logs. The audit trail must capture the subject's identity, the action, the affected object, and a timestamp, and it must be resistant to modification by the very users it records, or it fails as evidence.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>The most common trap in this objective swaps <strong>authentication</strong> and <strong>authorization</strong>. Authentication proves <em>identity</em>; authorization decides <em>permissions</em>. A perfectly authenticated user can still be denied access - being who you say you are does not entitle you to anything. If a question says a valid, logged-in user was blocked from a resource, the control at work is <strong>authorization</strong>, not authentication.</p></div><h3>Identity as the new perimeter</h3><p>In a cloud and remote-work world where the classic network perimeter has dissolved, identity has become the primary control plane - the idea captured by <span class='keyterm'>zero trust</span>, whose maxim is \"never trust, always verify.\" Under zero trust, no subject is trusted merely by network location; every request is authenticated, authorized against policy, and continuously evaluated. This elevates the AAA sequence from a login-time event to a continuous property: authorization may be re-checked mid-session as context (device posture, location, risk score) changes. The CISSP is expected to see identification-authentication-authorization not as a one-time gate but as a repeating loop enforced at every access.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Depends on</th><th>Undermined by</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Accountability</td><td>Unique IDs + auth + logs</td><td>Shared accounts, weak logging</td></tr><tr><td>Non-repudiation</td><td>Digital signatures, tamper-evident logs</td><td>Editable logs, no signing</td></tr><tr><td>Zero trust</td><td>Continuous auth + authz + telemetry</td><td>Implicit trust by location</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An investigation finds fraudulent transactions traced to the \"finance-svc\" service account, shared by four analysts with a static password stored in a wiki. The technical logs show the account did it, but the organization cannot attribute the act to a person - accountability has failed at the identification stage. Remediation replaces the shared account with individual, MFA-protected identities and a managed secret, restoring the ability to hold a specific human responsible.</p></div><h3>Why the sequence matters for design</h3><p>The strict ordering is not academic pedantry; it drives architecture. You cannot authorize before you authenticate, and you cannot hold anyone accountable if identification was never unique. Systems that grant access based on identification alone (\"I typed the manager's username\") are catastrophically broken because they skipped authentication. Systems that authenticate strongly but then grant blanket access have skipped meaningful authorization. And systems that do both well but log to a mutable file that admins can edit have undermined accountability. A CISSP evaluates any access-control design by walking these four stages in order and asking, at each, \"is this stage present, strong, and independent of the others?\"</p><h3>Mutual authentication and the impersonation problem</h3><p>A subtlety the CISSP must appreciate is that authentication should often be <em>mutual</em>: the server must also prove its identity to the client, not merely the reverse. One-way authentication - where only the user proves who they are - leaves the door open to <span class='keyterm'>impersonation</span> attacks in which a malicious server or phishing site masquerades as the legitimate one, harvests the user's credentials, and relays them onward. <span class='keyterm'>Mutual authentication</span>, implemented through mechanisms such as TLS server certificates, mutual TLS (client certificates), or the ticket exchange in Kerberos, closes this gap by requiring both parties to present verifiable evidence before trust is established. This is why phishing-resistant authenticators bind the credential to the legitimate origin - so a user cannot be tricked into authenticating to an impostor. The broader governance lesson is that authentication is not a property of a single actor but of a <em>relationship</em>: trust must be established bidirectionally for the channel to be safe, and a design that authenticates only the human while blindly trusting the endpoint has solved only half the problem.</p><h3>Authentication, authorization, and accounting as a protocol sequence</h3><p>It helps to see the four stages not merely as concepts but as an ordered exchange that a real AAA transaction performs, because the exam often frames a network-access scenario and asks which stage failed. Picture a laptop joining corporate Wi-Fi under 802.1X. First the supplicant asserts an identity (identification) to the authenticator, which relays it to a RADIUS server. The server challenges for and verifies a credential (authentication). On success, the server returns an authorization result - a VLAN assignment, an ACL, a session timeout - that dictates what the now-verified device may reach (authorization). Throughout the session the server records start, interim, and stop accounting records capturing bytes transferred and session duration (accounting), which later supports accountability. Map any access failure onto this sequence: a rejected password is an authentication failure; a verified user placed on a quarantine VLAN with no access to the resource is an authorization outcome, not an authentication problem; a session that cannot be attributed later is an accounting or logging gap. This protocol-level view turns the abstract four-stage model into a concrete diagnostic tool.</p><table><thead><tr><th>802.1X stage</th><th>AAA stage</th><th>What happens</th><th>Symptom if it fails</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Supplicant asserts identity</td><td>Identification</td><td>EAP identity sent to RADIUS</td><td>No response; access never starts</td></tr><tr><td>Credential challenge</td><td>Authentication</td><td>Password/cert/token verified</td><td>Access-Reject; login denied</td></tr><tr><td>Policy applied</td><td>Authorization</td><td>VLAN, ACL, timeout returned</td><td>Verified but wrong/limited access</td></tr><tr><td>Usage recorded</td><td>Accounting</td><td>Start/interim/stop records</td><td>No traceability of the session</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A contractor complains that after logging into the corporate network their laptop connects but cannot reach any internal server. The help desk assumes an authentication problem and resets the password repeatedly - to no effect, because authentication was never the issue. The RADIUS logs show an Access-Accept followed by assignment to a restricted guest VLAN: the contractor was <strong>authenticated</strong> successfully but <strong>authorized</strong> only for internet access by policy. Correctly locating the failure at the authorization stage - not authentication - is exactly the discrimination the exam rewards, and it points the fix at the network-access policy rather than the credential.</p></div><h3>Continuous authentication and the death of the perimeter</h3><p>Classic designs treated authentication as a one-time gate: prove yourself at login and enjoy trust for the rest of the session. <span class='keyterm'>Continuous authentication</span> rejects that assumption, re-evaluating identity and risk throughout a session using signals such as device posture, geolocation, behavioral biometrics, and network context, and stepping up or terminating the session when the signals shift. This is the operational heart of <span class='keyterm'>zero trust</span>: rather than trusting a subject because it once authenticated or because it sits inside a trusted network, every request is treated as originating from a hostile network and is authenticated and authorized against policy on its own merits. The practical consequence is that the four-stage sequence becomes a loop that runs continuously rather than a gate that fires once, and authorization decisions can be revoked mid-session the instant risk rises. For the exam, the tell is any scenario emphasizing that trust is never permanent and must be re-earned per request - that is continuous authentication expressing zero trust, and it explains why modern IAM instruments telemetry as heavily as it instruments the login itself.</p><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>Beyond the authentication/authorization swap, students often assume \"accounting\" and \"accountability\" are unrelated - they are two faces of the same third A, one the protocol mechanism and one the governance goal. Another misconception is that identification requires secrecy; usernames are public claims and that is fine - the secrecy requirement belongs to authentication. A third is assuming authentication is one-way; without mutual authentication a user can be lured into proving themselves to an impostor. Finally, some treat the audit trail as an afterthought, but without a protected, attributable log the entire chain of identification and authentication produces no accountability at all, which is precisely the outcome regulators and forensic investigators find unacceptable.</p>"},
  {heading:"Authentication Factors, MFA & Biometrics", body:"<p>Authentication strength is a function of the <span class='keyterm'>factors</span> it uses and how independent they are. CISSP organizes authentication evidence into three canonical types, plus two contextual extensions, and expects you to reason about the error rates of biometric systems well enough to interpret a comparison table. This section covers the factor taxonomy, multifactor design, the biometric accuracy metrics, and the modern push toward passwordless authentication.</p><h3>The three (plus two) factors</h3><p>The classic factors are <span class='keyterm'>Type 1 - something you know</span> (knowledge: password, PIN, passphrase, security question); <span class='keyterm'>Type 2 - something you have</span> (possession: smart card, hardware token, phone with an authenticator app); and <span class='keyterm'>Type 3 - something you are</span> (biometric: fingerprint, iris, face, palm vein). Two contextual extensions are often added: <span class='keyterm'>somewhere you are</span> (location, geofencing, source IP) and <span class='keyterm'>something you do</span> (behavioral biometrics such as typing rhythm, gait, or signature dynamics). True <span class='keyterm'>multifactor authentication (MFA)</span> requires factors from <em>different types</em>. Two passwords are not MFA; a password plus an SMS code plus a security question is still only two types (know + have), because two of them are knowledge.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Factor type</th><th>Category</th><th>Examples</th><th>Primary weakness</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Type 1 - know</td><td>Knowledge</td><td>Password, PIN, passphrase</td><td>Phishing, guessing, reuse</td></tr><tr><td>Type 2 - have</td><td>Possession</td><td>Smart card, TOTP token, phone</td><td>Theft, loss, SIM-swap</td></tr><tr><td>Type 3 - are</td><td>Biometric</td><td>Fingerprint, iris, face, vein</td><td>Cannot be reissued, spoofing</td></tr><tr><td>Somewhere you are</td><td>Location</td><td>Geolocation, IP, geofence</td><td>Spoofable, coarse</td></tr><tr><td>Something you do</td><td>Behavioral</td><td>Keystroke, gait, signature</td><td>Variable, higher error rates</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why MFA works and where it breaks</h3><p>MFA raises the attacker's cost because compromising two independent factors is far harder than one - a phished password is useless without the physical token. But independence is the operative word. SMS one-time codes are the weakest \"have\" factor because they are vulnerable to <span class='keyterm'>SIM-swapping</span> and SS7 interception, and push-approval MFA is defeated by <span class='keyterm'>MFA fatigue</span> attacks where the attacker spams approval prompts until a tired user taps yes. Phishing-resistant MFA - <span class='keyterm'>FIDO2/WebAuthn</span> hardware authenticators bound to the origin - is the current gold standard because the credential cannot be replayed to a fake site. The CISSP framing is that not all MFA is equal, and the choice of second factor is a risk decision.</p><h3>Biometric accuracy: FAR, FRR, and the crossover</h3><p>Biometric systems never give a perfect yes/no; they compute a similarity score against a stored template and compare it to a threshold. This produces two error types. The <span class='keyterm'>False Acceptance Rate (FAR)</span>, or Type II error, is the rate at which an <em>impostor</em> is wrongly accepted - a security failure. The <span class='keyterm'>False Rejection Rate (FRR)</span>, or Type I error, is the rate at which a <em>legitimate user</em> is wrongly rejected - a usability failure. The two trade off against each other: tighten the threshold to lower FAR and you raise FRR, and vice versa. The <span class='keyterm'>Crossover Error Rate (CER)</span>, also called the <span class='keyterm'>Equal Error Rate (EER)</span>, is the threshold at which FAR equals FRR, and it is the single best figure of merit for comparing biometric systems - lower CER means a better system overall.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Also called</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Consequence</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>FAR</td><td>Type II error</td><td>Impostor accepted</td><td>Security breach</td></tr><tr><td>FRR</td><td>Type I error</td><td>Valid user rejected</td><td>Frustration, lockout</td></tr><tr><td>CER / EER</td><td>Crossover / equal error rate</td><td>FAR = FRR threshold</td><td>Lower is a better system</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Memorize the direction: <strong>FAR is the dangerous one</strong> (an impostor gets in - Type II), <strong>FRR is the annoying one</strong> (a valid user is turned away - Type I). To compare two biometric products, compare their <strong>CER/EER</strong> - the lower, the better. For a high-security vault you deliberately accept a higher FRR to drive FAR down; for a convenience application you accept a higher FAR to reduce FRR. The tuning knob is the threshold.</p></div><h3>Biometric enrollment and its special risks</h3><p>Biometrics carry a unique liability: they are <em>not revocable</em>. A breached password is changed in seconds; a stolen fingerprint template is compromised forever, because you cannot reissue your finger. This is why biometric templates must be stored as encrypted, non-reversible representations, ideally in a secure enclave, never as raw images. Enrollment quality also matters - a poorly captured template inflates both error rates. Additional metrics the exam may reference include <span class='keyterm'>throughput</span> (how many users the system can process per minute) and user acceptance (people resist iris and retina scanners as intrusive). No biometric should be a sole factor for high-value access precisely because of the irrevocability problem; it belongs as one factor within MFA.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A bank tunes its facial-recognition login for customer convenience and sets a loose threshold. Fraud rises as impostors using photos and deepfakes are accepted - the FAR was set too high. Security re-tightens the threshold (accepting more legitimate-user rejections, a higher FRR) and adds a possession factor, converting a single weak biometric into phishing-resistant MFA. The lesson: a biometric alone is a convenience feature, not strong authentication.</p></div><h3>Passwordless and the future of authentication</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Passwordless</span> authentication removes the knowledge factor entirely, replacing it with possession plus biometric - for example a <span class='keyterm'>passkey</span> (a FIDO2 credential) unlocked by the device's fingerprint sensor. This is both more secure (nothing phishable to steal) and more usable (nothing to remember), which is why it is displacing passwords for high-assurance access. The CISSP should understand passwordless not as \"no authentication\" but as strong, phishing-resistant, multi-type authentication where the secret never leaves the device and is never transmitted.</p><h3>OTP mechanics: HOTP versus TOTP</h3><p>The possession factor most people encounter is the <span class='keyterm'>one-time password (OTP)</span>, and the CISSP should distinguish its two algorithms. <span class='keyterm'>HOTP</span> (HMAC-based OTP) derives each code from a shared secret and an incrementing <em>counter</em>, so codes are used in sequence and remain valid until used - which can drift out of sync if a user generates codes without submitting them. <span class='keyterm'>TOTP</span> (time-based OTP) replaces the counter with the current <em>time</em> in fixed windows (typically 30 seconds), so each code is valid only briefly - the mechanism behind authenticator apps like Google Authenticator. TOTP's short validity window sharply limits replay, which is why it has largely displaced HOTP for interactive login. Both are far stronger than SMS delivery because the secret never traverses the network at authentication time - the code is computed locally on the device from a secret provisioned once at enrollment. Still, neither is fully phishing-resistant: a user can be tricked into typing a live TOTP code into a fake site within its window, which is precisely the gap that origin-bound FIDO2 credentials close by refusing to release to any origin but the legitimate one.</p><h3>Working the biometric math</h3><p>The exam may hand you numbers and ask you to reason, so practice the arithmetic of biometric error. Suppose a fingerprint reader guarding a data center is measured at a threshold where its <span class='keyterm'>FAR</span> is 0.001 (0.1 percent) and its <span class='keyterm'>FRR</span> is 0.03 (3 percent). Over 10,000 impostor attempts you would expect roughly ten false acceptances - ten intruders wrongly admitted - which for a high-security space is unacceptable, so you tighten the threshold. Tightening lowers FAR toward, say, 0.0001 but simultaneously drives FRR up to perhaps 8 percent, meaning 800 of 10,000 legitimate entries per period are wrongly rejected and staff grow frustrated. The <span class='keyterm'>CER</span> is the single threshold where the two curves intersect and FAR equals FRR; a reader with a CER of 1 percent is unambiguously better than one with a CER of 3 percent because at its balance point it errs less often in both directions. The practical takeaway is that FAR and FRR are not independent dials you set freely - they move inversely along one threshold, and the CER summarizes the whole trade-off in a single comparable figure.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Setting</th><th>Threshold</th><th>FAR (security risk)</th><th>FRR (usability cost)</th><th>Right for</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Convenience login</td><td>Loose</td><td>Higher</td><td>Lower</td><td>Consumer phone unlock</td></tr><tr><td>Balanced (CER point)</td><td>At crossover</td><td>= FRR</td><td>= FAR</td><td>Benchmark comparison</td></tr><tr><td>High-security vault</td><td>Tight</td><td>Very low</td><td>Higher (accepted)</td><td>Data center, SCIF</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>If a question gives you two biometric readers and asks which is better <em>overall</em>, compare the <strong>CER/EER</strong> and pick the lower one - do not be distracted by a single flattering FAR or FRR figure measured at an unstated threshold. If it asks which reader suits a <em>high-security</em> deployment, choose the one you can tune to the <strong>lowest FAR</strong>, accepting the higher FRR as the price of keeping impostors out. FAR is the number that gets you breached; FRR is the number that gets you help-desk tickets.</p></div><h3>Behavioral biometrics and liveness detection</h3><p>Beyond the physiological Type 3 factors, the CISSP should recognize <span class='keyterm'>behavioral biometrics</span> - the \"something you do\" extension that measures <em>how</em> a person acts rather than a static physical trait. Keystroke dynamics profile typing rhythm and dwell time; mouse and touch dynamics profile cursor movement; gait analysis profiles walking pattern; and voice and signature dynamics profile speech and pen motion. Their appeal is that they can run <em>continuously</em> and passively in the background, feeding the continuous-authentication engine without interrupting the user. Their weakness is higher variability - fatigue, injury, or a different keyboard shift the pattern - so they carry elevated FRR and are used as one signal among many rather than a sole gate. A parallel defense is <span class='keyterm'>liveness detection</span>, which counters <span class='keyterm'>presentation attacks</span> (spoofing) - a photograph, mask, deepfake, or gelatin fingerprint presented to fool a Type 3 sensor. Liveness checks look for pulse, blink, depth, or challenge-response motion to confirm a live human is present, and their absence is exactly why a facial or fingerprint reader without anti-spoofing is trivially defeated. The exam framing is that a biometric's real-world strength depends not only on its FAR/FRR at the sensor but on whether it resists presentation attacks at all.</p><th>Based on</th><th>Validity</th><th>Weakness</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>HOTP</td><td>Counter + shared secret</td><td>Until used (sequential)</td><td>Counter drift; longer exposure</td></tr><tr><td>TOTP</td><td>Time window + shared secret</td><td>~30 seconds</td><td>Real-time phishing within window</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>The dominant misconception is that any two credentials constitute MFA; two knowledge factors (password + security question) are single-factor. Another is reversing FAR and FRR under pressure - drill the mnemonic that False <em>Acceptance</em> accepts the wrong person. A third is treating all MFA as equally strong when SMS and push are materially weaker than FIDO2 hardware, and even TOTP is phishable in real time. Finally, students underestimate the irrevocability of biometrics, treating a fingerprint like a password that can simply be reset - it cannot, which is exactly why template protection and multifactor context matter so much.</p>"},
  {heading:"Identity Proofing, Registration & Session Management", body:"<p>Strong authentication is worthless if the wrong person was enrolled in the first place. This section covers the front of the identity lifecycle - <span class='keyterm'>enrollment</span>, <span class='keyterm'>identity proofing</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>credential issuance</span> - and the ongoing control of authenticated sessions through <span class='keyterm'>timeout</span> and <span class='keyterm'>reauthentication</span>. NIST SP 800-63 is the canonical reference the CISSP should recognize by name, with its separation of identity assurance from authentication assurance.</p><h3>Identity proofing and registration</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Identity proofing</span> is the process of verifying that a person is who they claim to be <em>before</em> a credential is issued - binding a real-world identity to a digital one. It runs during <span class='keyterm'>registration</span> (enrollment) and typically involves resolving the claimed identity to a single person, validating supporting evidence (a passport, driver's license, utility bill), and verifying that the applicant is the legitimate holder of that evidence (a liveness check, a knowledge-based challenge, or an in-person appearance). Weak proofing is the root cause of account-takeover and synthetic-identity fraud: if an attacker can enroll as someone else, no downstream authentication strength can save you. NIST expresses proofing rigor as <span class='keyterm'>Identity Assurance Levels (IAL1, IAL2, IAL3)</span>, from self-asserted through remote evidence verification to in-person or supervised proofing.</p><table><thead><tr><th>NIST assurance model</th><th>Governs</th><th>Levels</th><th>Increasing rigor</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>IAL - Identity Assurance</td><td>How well the identity was proofed</td><td>IAL1 / IAL2 / IAL3</td><td>Self-asserted &rarr; remote evidence &rarr; in-person</td></tr><tr><td>AAL - Authenticator Assurance</td><td>Strength of the authentication</td><td>AAL1 / AAL2 / AAL3</td><td>Single-factor &rarr; MFA &rarr; hardware, phishing-resistant</td></tr><tr><td>FAL - Federation Assurance</td><td>Strength of federated assertions</td><td>FAL1 / FAL2 / FAL3</td><td>Bearer &rarr; encrypted &rarr; holder-of-key</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Credential issuance and management</h3><p>Once proofing succeeds, a <span class='keyterm'>credential</span> is issued and bound to the subscriber - a password set, a certificate provisioned, a smart card personalized, or a passkey registered. The <span class='keyterm'>credential lifecycle</span> continues well past issuance: credentials must be renewed, rotated, suspended when a device is lost, and revoked at deprovisioning. A certificate has an explicit validity period and a revocation mechanism (CRL or OCSP); a smart card can be deactivated; a password has a rotation and complexity policy. The exam-relevant governance point is that issuance is not a one-time act but the start of a managed lifecycle, and gaps in that lifecycle - unrevoked certificates, orphaned tokens - are exploitable.</p><h3>Session management</h3><p>Authentication establishes a <span class='keyterm'>session</span> - a period during which the system trusts the authenticated identity without re-prompting. Because a live session is a standing grant of access, it must be governed. <span class='keyterm'>Session timeout</span> ends a session after a period of inactivity (idle timeout) or after a maximum absolute duration, limiting the window in which a hijacked or abandoned session can be abused. <span class='keyterm'>Reauthentication</span> forces the user to prove identity again for sensitive actions (a step-up challenge before a wire transfer) or when risk signals change. The <span class='keyterm'>session identifier</span> - typically a token or cookie - is a bearer credential and must be protected: generated with strong randomness, transmitted only over TLS, marked HttpOnly and Secure, and invalidated server-side at logout.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Session control</th><th>Protects against</th><th>Mechanism</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Idle timeout</td><td>Walk-away / abandoned session</td><td>Expire after N minutes inactive</td></tr><tr><td>Absolute timeout</td><td>Long-lived hijacked session</td><td>Hard cap on total duration</td></tr><tr><td>Reauthentication / step-up</td><td>Sensitive-action abuse</td><td>Re-prompt for high-risk operations</td></tr><tr><td>Secure session token</td><td>Session hijacking / fixation</td><td>Random, TLS-only, HttpOnly, server-invalidated</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Do not confuse <strong>IAL</strong> (how well you proved the identity at enrollment) with <strong>AAL</strong> (how strong the authentication is at login). A bank can require in-person proofing (high IAL) yet allow a simple password (low AAL), or accept weak proofing but demand hardware MFA - the two dials are independent. When a scenario turns on <em>how the account was originally established</em>, the concept is <strong>identity proofing / IAL</strong>, not authentication strength.</p></div><h3>Session hijacking and fixation</h3><p>Two attacks the CISSP must recognize target the session rather than the login. <span class='keyterm'>Session hijacking</span> steals a valid session token (via cross-site scripting, packet capture on unencrypted links, or malware) and replays it to impersonate the user without ever knowing the password. <span class='keyterm'>Session fixation</span> tricks a victim into using a session ID the attacker already knows, then rides that session after the victim authenticates. Defenses converge: encrypt all traffic, regenerate the session ID upon privilege change (especially at login), bind sessions to contextual signals, set short timeouts, and invalidate tokens server-side on logout rather than merely deleting the client cookie.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A brokerage lets sessions live for eight hours with no idle timeout. A user leaves a logged-in workstation at a shared desk; a passerby executes trades under the live session. The fix is layered: a fifteen-minute idle timeout, an absolute session cap, and <strong>reauthentication</strong> (step-up) before any trade executes - so even a captured session cannot move money without a fresh proof of identity.</p></div><h3>Federated and provisioned identities at enrollment</h3><p>Enrollment is not always local. In federated and cloud environments, identities may be provisioned in bulk from an authoritative HR source (see the provisioning lifecycle section) or established just-in-time on first federated login. Even then, the proofing question persists: the assurance of a federated identity is only as strong as the proofing the identity provider performed, which is why <span class='keyterm'>Federation Assurance Level (FAL)</span> and trust agreements between relying parties matter. A CISSP evaluating a federation asks not just \"is the assertion cryptographically valid\" but \"how rigorously did the upstream IdP proof this person, and do I trust that.\"</p><h3>Account recovery: the weakest link</h3><p>The most overlooked part of the credential lifecycle is <span class='keyterm'>account recovery</span> - the path a legitimate user takes when they lose their authenticator. Recovery is a perennial security weak point because it is, by design, an alternative route to authentication that bypasses the primary factor, and attackers target it precisely for that reason. Weak recovery relying on <span class='keyterm'>knowledge-based authentication</span> (mother's maiden name, first pet) is trivially defeated because the answers are researchable or breached; strong recovery re-runs proofing at a level commensurate with the account's value - re-verifying government ID, sending a code to a previously enrolled and verified channel, or requiring in-person re-proofing for high-assurance accounts. The governing principle is that the recovery path must be <em>no weaker than the primary authentication it restores</em>, because the overall strength of an authentication system is the strength of its weakest entry point, and recovery is almost always that point. A system with hardware MFA and an email-reset backdoor is only as strong as that email account. CISSP-level design therefore treats recovery as a first-class control subject to the same assurance analysis as login itself, complete with alerting on recovery events for sensitive accounts.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A cloud administrator protected by a FIDO2 security key loses the key while traveling. The recovery process only requires answering two knowledge questions and a code to a personal email, both of which an attacker has already compromised. The attacker recovers the account and inherits full admin rights, entirely bypassing the strong primary factor. The remediation makes high-value recovery require a supervised re-proofing plus a code to an out-of-band channel, and alerts the SOC on every privileged recovery attempt.</p></div><h3>Mapping NIST 800-63 levels to real deployments</h3><p>The three assurance dimensions of <span class='keyterm'>NIST SP 800-63</span> - IAL, AAL, and FAL - are chosen independently to match an application's risk, and the CISSP should be able to reason about a concrete combination rather than merely recite the levels. Consider three services. A public newsletter signup needs no proofing (<span class='keyterm'>IAL1</span>, self-asserted) and a single password (<span class='keyterm'>AAL1</span>) - risk is negligible, so friction should be near zero. A consumer bank must resolve you to a real person via remote evidence such as a photographed ID plus a liveness selfie (<span class='keyterm'>IAL2</span>) and require phishing-resistant MFA (<span class='keyterm'>AAL2</span> or AAL3) because money moves. A government system granting access to classified or life-safety data demands in-person or supervised remote proofing (<span class='keyterm'>IAL3</span>) and a hardware, phishing-resistant authenticator with verifier-impersonation resistance (<span class='keyterm'>AAL3</span>), and if the identity is asserted across agencies it needs a holder-of-key federated assertion (<span class='keyterm'>FAL3</span>) rather than a simple bearer token. The pattern to internalize is that rising real-world consequence pushes all three dials upward, but each dial answers a different question and can be set separately.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Service</th><th>IAL (proofing)</th><th>AAL (authenticator)</th><th>FAL (federation)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Newsletter signup</td><td>IAL1 self-asserted</td><td>AAL1 single-factor</td><td>n/a or FAL1 bearer</td></tr><tr><td>Consumer bank</td><td>IAL2 remote evidence</td><td>AAL2 MFA</td><td>FAL2 encrypted assertion</td></tr><tr><td>Classified system</td><td>IAL3 in-person</td><td>AAL3 hardware, phishing-resistant</td><td>FAL3 holder-of-key</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>When a stem describes <em>how the applicant proved they are a real, specific person</em>, it is testing <strong>IAL</strong>. When it describes <em>the strength and number of factors at each login</em>, it is testing <strong>AAL</strong>. When it describes <em>how an identity assertion is protected as it crosses between an IdP and a relying party</em>, it is testing <strong>FAL</strong>. These three are set independently - a high IAL never implies a high AAL, and vice versa - so beware any answer that assumes one forces the other.</p></div><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>A common mistake is thinking strong authentication compensates for weak proofing - it does not, because you would simply be strongly authenticating an impostor who enrolled fraudulently. Another is treating a session as stateless once granted; a live session is continuous authorization and must be time-bounded and re-validated. A third is hardening login while leaving a weak recovery path, which merely relocates the attack. Finally, students often protect the login but forget the token: an application with flawless MFA and an insecure, non-expiring session cookie has merely moved the attack from the front door to an open window.</p>"},
  {heading:"Federated Identity & Single Sign-On", body:"<p>As organizations sprawl across dozens of on-premise and cloud applications, forcing users to maintain a credential per system is both insecure and unusable. <span class='keyterm'>Single sign-on (SSO)</span> and <span class='keyterm'>federated identity</span> solve this by centralizing authentication so one login grants access to many services. The CISSP must distinguish the protocols - <span class='keyterm'>SAML</span>, <span class='keyterm'>OpenID Connect (OIDC)</span>, <span class='keyterm'>OAuth 2.0</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>Kerberos</span> - and reason about the trade-offs of on-premise, cloud, and hybrid federation topologies.</p><h3>SSO versus federation</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>SSO</span> lets a user authenticate once and access multiple applications within a single security domain without re-authenticating. <span class='keyterm'>Federation</span> extends that trust <em>across</em> organizational or domain boundaries: a user authenticated by their home <span class='keyterm'>identity provider (IdP)</span> is trusted by a separate <span class='keyterm'>relying party (RP)</span> or <span class='keyterm'>service provider (SP)</span> without the RP ever holding the user's credentials. The enabling idea is that the RP outsources authentication to a trusted IdP and receives a signed <em>assertion</em> or token attesting to the user's identity and attributes. The benefits are fewer passwords, centralized policy and MFA enforcement, and instant deprovisioning at the IdP; the risk is concentration - the IdP becomes a single point of both failure and compromise.</p><h3>SAML, OIDC, and OAuth 2.0</h3><p>These three are constantly confused, and the exam rewards a crisp separation. <span class='keyterm'>SAML</span> (Security Assertion Markup Language) is an XML-based standard for exchanging authentication and authorization assertions between an IdP and an SP - the workhorse of enterprise web SSO. <span class='keyterm'>OAuth 2.0</span> is an <em>authorization</em> framework, not an authentication protocol: it lets a user delegate limited access to their resources (grant an app permission to read your calendar) via <span class='keyterm'>access tokens</span> and <span class='keyterm'>scopes</span>, without sharing a password. <span class='keyterm'>OpenID Connect (OIDC)</span> is a thin identity layer built <em>on top of</em> OAuth 2.0 that adds an <span class='keyterm'>ID token</span> (a signed JWT) to actually authenticate the user - it is the modern standard for consumer and API-driven SSO.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Protocol</th><th>Primary purpose</th><th>Format</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SAML 2.0</td><td>Authentication + authorization assertions</td><td>XML</td><td>Enterprise web SSO</td></tr><tr><td>OAuth 2.0</td><td>Delegated authorization (not authN)</td><td>Tokens / JSON</td><td>API access delegation</td></tr><tr><td>OIDC</td><td>Authentication layer on OAuth 2.0</td><td>JWT (ID token)</td><td>Modern app / mobile SSO</td></tr><tr><td>Kerberos</td><td>Ticket-based network authentication</td><td>Tickets</td><td>On-prem AD domains</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Burn in one distinction: <strong>OAuth is authorization</strong> (what an app may do on your behalf), <strong>OIDC is authentication</strong> (who you are, layered on OAuth). Using bare OAuth 2.0 as a login mechanism is a classic design error because OAuth never proves identity - that is exactly the gap OIDC's ID token fills. <strong>SAML</strong> is the enterprise XML equivalent that does both authN and authZ in one assertion.</p></div><h3>Kerberos: the on-premise standard</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Kerberos</span> is the ticket-based authentication protocol underlying Active Directory domains. A user authenticates once to the <span class='keyterm'>Key Distribution Center (KDC)</span> and receives a <span class='keyterm'>Ticket-Granting Ticket (TGT)</span>; to reach a service, the client presents the TGT to obtain a <span class='keyterm'>service ticket</span>, which it hands to the target service. Because tickets are time-stamped and encrypted with keys the parties share with the KDC, credentials never traverse the wire in reusable form - achieving on-premise SSO. Its dependence on synchronized clocks and a highly available KDC is a design constraint, and its ticket model is a rich attack surface (covered in the Kerberos-internals section). Kerberos exemplifies domain-internal SSO, whereas SAML/OIDC extend trust across the internet.</p><h3>On-premise, cloud, and hybrid federation</h3><p>The topology of federation is itself a governance decision. <span class='keyterm'>On-premise federation</span> keeps the IdP inside the corporate data center (classic ADFS), giving full control but requiring the organization to run and secure the infrastructure. <span class='keyterm'>Cloud federation</span> uses an <span class='keyterm'>Identity-as-a-Service (IDaaS)</span> provider (Azure AD/Entra, Okta, Ping) as the IdP, outsourcing availability and scale but placing critical identity infrastructure with a third party. <span class='keyterm'>Hybrid federation</span> bridges the two - synchronizing on-prem directories to a cloud IdP so a single identity works across legacy and SaaS - which is the common enterprise reality and also the most complex to secure because trust and synchronization span two domains.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Topology</th><th>IdP location</th><th>Strength</th><th>Trade-off</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>On-premise</td><td>Corporate data center</td><td>Full control, data stays local</td><td>You run and secure it; scaling burden</td></tr><tr><td>Cloud (IDaaS)</td><td>Third-party provider</td><td>Scale, availability, less to run</td><td>Critical identity in a vendor's hands</td></tr><tr><td>Hybrid</td><td>On-prem synced to cloud</td><td>One identity across legacy + SaaS</td><td>Complex trust and sync to secure</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A company adopts fifty SaaS apps and integrates each with an IDaaS IdP via SAML/OIDC. When an employee is terminated, disabling their single IdP account instantly revokes access to all fifty - a deprovisioning win. But the security team notes the IdP is now a crown jewel: a compromise of that one account, or of the IdP itself, would unlock everything. They mandate phishing-resistant MFA, conditional access, and privileged-access controls specifically around the federation infrastructure.</p></div><h3>Trust, assertions, and their risks</h3><p>Federation runs on cryptographically signed <em>assertions</em>, and their integrity is everything. A relying party must validate the signature, issuer, audience, and expiry of every SAML assertion or OIDC ID token, or it can be tricked by forged or replayed tokens. Misconfigured trust - accepting assertions from an untrusted issuer, failing to validate the audience, or allowing algorithm downgrade - has produced real-world SSO bypasses. The CISSP treats the trust relationship between IdP and RP as a governed contract with security requirements, not a checkbox, and understands that the convenience of SSO concentrates risk that must be counterbalanced with strong controls on the IdP.</p><h3>SPML, WS-Federation, and the standards landscape</h3><p>SAML and OIDC dominate, but the CISSP should recognize the broader federation and identity-standards landscape so that an unfamiliar acronym in a question does not derail an answer. <span class='keyterm'>WS-Federation</span> is a Microsoft-aligned federation standard, part of the WS-* family, historically used with ADFS alongside SAML. <span class='keyterm'>SPML</span> (Service Provisioning Markup Language) was an early XML standard for provisioning accounts across domains, largely superseded by the simpler REST-based SCIM. On the authorization side, <span class='keyterm'>XACML</span> expresses fine-grained attribute-based policy. The pattern to internalize is that these standards divide cleanly by <em>function</em>: SAML/OIDC/WS-Federation handle <em>authentication and assertion</em>, SCIM/SPML handle <em>account provisioning</em>, and OAuth/XACML handle <em>authorization</em>. When a scenario names a standard, first ask which of these three jobs it does; that alone eliminates most wrong answers. The convergence trend is toward JSON/REST standards (OIDC, SCIM) displacing the older XML/SOAP ones (SAML, SPML, WS-*) for new deployments, though enterprise environments run both for years because legacy applications remain SAML-only.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Standard</th><th>Function</th><th>Style</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SAML / WS-Federation</td><td>Authentication assertion</td><td>XML / SOAP (legacy)</td></tr><tr><td>OIDC</td><td>Authentication</td><td>JSON / REST (modern)</td></tr><tr><td>SCIM / SPML</td><td>Account provisioning</td><td>REST / XML</td></tr><tr><td>OAuth 2.0 / XACML</td><td>Authorization</td><td>Token / policy</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>A SAML SSO handshake, step by step</h3><p>Because the exam frequently narrates a federated login and asks where trust is established or broken, walk through a concrete <span class='keyterm'>SP-initiated SAML</span> flow. (1) A user browses to a SaaS application (the service provider) and requests a protected page. (2) The SP, finding no active session, generates a <span class='keyterm'>SAML authentication request</span> (AuthnRequest) and redirects the browser to the user's identity provider. (3) The IdP authenticates the user - prompting for password and MFA if no IdP session exists - and, on success, constructs a signed <span class='keyterm'>SAML assertion</span> containing the user's identifier, attributes, and the conditions of use (audience, validity window). (4) The IdP returns the assertion to the browser, which POSTs it to the SP's <span class='keyterm'>Assertion Consumer Service</span>. (5) The SP validates the signature against the IdP's known certificate, checks the issuer, audience, and NotOnOrAfter expiry, and only then establishes a local session and serves the page. The crucial security insight is that the SP never sees the user's password; it trusts a cryptographically signed statement from an IdP it has a pre-established trust relationship with. Every real-world SAML bypass traces to a skipped validation in step 5 - an unchecked signature, a missing audience restriction, or an accepted expired assertion.</p><table><thead><tr><th>OIDC term</th><th>SAML equivalent</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>OpenID Provider (OP)</td><td>Identity Provider (IdP)</td><td>Authenticates the user</td></tr><tr><td>Relying Party (RP)</td><td>Service Provider (SP)</td><td>Consumes the identity assertion</td></tr><tr><td>ID token (JWT)</td><td>SAML assertion</td><td>Signed statement of who the user is</td></tr><tr><td>Authorization endpoint</td><td>SSO / redirect endpoint</td><td>Where the login request is sent</td></tr><tr><td>Redirect URI callback</td><td>Assertion Consumer Service</td><td>Where the assertion is delivered</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>In any federated-login question, the relying party's job is to <strong>validate the assertion</strong> - signature, issuer, audience, and expiry - before granting a session. If a scenario describes a forged or replayed login, suspect a <strong>missing validation</strong> at the consuming service, not a stolen password. And remember the vocabulary maps cleanly: <strong>IdP/OP</strong> proves identity, <strong>SP/RP</strong> consumes it, and the <strong>assertion/ID token</strong> is the signed evidence passed between them.</p></div><p>One further nuance the CISSP should hold is the difference between <span class='keyterm'>SP-initiated</span> and <span class='keyterm'>IdP-initiated</span> flows. In the SP-initiated case above, the user starts at the application and is redirected to the IdP to authenticate. In the IdP-initiated case, the user first authenticates at a portal hosted by the identity provider and then launches applications from a tile or menu, so the assertion is pushed to the SP without a prior AuthnRequest. IdP-initiated flows are convenient but carry a subtle risk - because the SP receives an unsolicited assertion, it cannot correlate it to a request it made, which historically enabled certain assertion-replay and cross-site request attacks unless the SP rigorously enforces one-time-use and tight expiry. This is why security guidance generally prefers SP-initiated flows, and why the exam may reward recognizing that an unsolicited, replayable assertion is more dangerous than one tied to a specific outstanding request.</p><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>The headline misconception is using OAuth as login - it authorizes, it does not authenticate, which is why OIDC exists. Another is equating SSO with federation; SSO is single-domain convenience, federation crosses trust boundaries. A third is assuming cloud federation is inherently less secure than on-prem - each simply relocates the risk, and a well-run IDaaS often exceeds an under-resourced on-prem ADFS. Finally, remember that SSO's great strength - one login for everything - is also its great danger, making the IdP the highest-value target in the environment.</p>"},
  {heading:"Credential & Directory Services Management", body:"<p>Behind every authentication decision sits a store of identities and credentials that must itself be managed, secured, and kept accurate. This section covers <span class='keyterm'>directory services</span> (LDAP and Active Directory), <span class='keyterm'>just-in-time provisioning</span>, <span class='keyterm'>password vaults</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>self-service</span> - the plumbing that makes identity operational at scale. The governance theme is that a directory is a high-value asset whose integrity underpins the entire IAM program.</p><h3>Directory services: LDAP and Active Directory</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>directory service</span> is a hierarchical database of identities, groups, and attributes optimized for high-volume reads. <span class='keyterm'>LDAP</span> (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) is the standard protocol for querying and modifying directories; it organizes entries in a tree (the <span class='keyterm'>Directory Information Tree</span>) using distinguished names. <span class='keyterm'>Active Directory (AD)</span> is Microsoft's directory service, which uses LDAP for directory access, Kerberos for authentication, and DNS for locating services, organizing objects into domains, trees, and forests with <span class='keyterm'>Organizational Units (OUs)</span> and <span class='keyterm'>Group Policy</span> for centralized control. The directory is the authoritative source of truth for identity, which is precisely why compromising a domain controller (which holds AD) is the classic attacker end-goal - it yields the keys to every identity in the domain.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Element</th><th>Role</th><th>Note</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>LDAP</td><td>Protocol to read/write the directory</td><td>Use LDAPS (over TLS) - plain LDAP is cleartext</td></tr><tr><td>Active Directory</td><td>Microsoft directory service</td><td>LDAP + Kerberos + DNS + Group Policy</td></tr><tr><td>Domain controller</td><td>Server hosting AD</td><td>Top attacker target; protect ruthlessly</td></tr><tr><td>Organizational Unit</td><td>Container for delegation/policy</td><td>Enables least-privilege administration</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Provisioning and just-in-time access</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Provisioning</span> creates and populates identity records and their access rights. Traditional provisioning creates accounts in advance from an authoritative HR feed, but this leaves standing accounts and standing privilege. <span class='keyterm'>Just-in-time (JIT) provisioning</span> creates the account or grants the entitlement only at the moment of first need - for example, a federated user's account is created in a SaaS app the first time they log in via SSO, or an administrator is granted elevated rights only for the duration of an approved task. JIT reduces the attack surface by eliminating dormant, over-privileged accounts, and it pairs naturally with the least-privilege and zero-standing-privilege philosophies. The exam contrasts JIT (grant on demand, revoke automatically) with the risk of persistent, always-on access.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Just-in-time provisioning</strong> grants access only when needed and removes it automatically afterward, shrinking the window of exposure. When a scenario worries about standing privileged accounts or dormant entitlements that attackers could exploit, JIT (and zero standing privilege) is the design answer. It is the provisioning counterpart to least privilege applied across <em>time</em>, not just scope.</p></div><h3>Password vaults and credential stores</h3><p>Humans cannot remember dozens of strong, unique passwords, and applications should never hold credentials in plaintext, so credentials are consolidated into secured stores. A <span class='keyterm'>password vault</span> (password manager) encrypts a user's credentials under a master secret, enabling strong, unique passwords per site without memorization. At the enterprise and machine level, a <span class='keyterm'>secrets manager</span> or <span class='keyterm'>privileged credential vault</span> stores service-account passwords, API keys, and certificates, brokering and rotating them so no human ever sees or reuses a static secret. These vaults are themselves the highest-value target, so they are protected with strong master authentication, encryption at rest, access logging, and (for privileged vaults) automatic rotation and session brokering.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Store type</th><th>Protects</th><th>Key control</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Personal password vault</td><td>A user's site passwords</td><td>Master password + MFA, local encryption</td></tr><tr><td>Enterprise secrets manager</td><td>App/service credentials, API keys</td><td>Automated rotation, no plaintext in code</td></tr><tr><td>Privileged credential vault (PAM)</td><td>Admin/service-account passwords</td><td>Check-out, rotation, session recording</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Self-service identity management</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Self-service</span> capabilities let users manage routine identity tasks without a help-desk ticket - most importantly <span class='keyterm'>self-service password reset (SSPR)</span>, but also profile updates, group membership requests, and access requests routed for approval. Self-service reduces cost and speeds users along, but it introduces a security paradox: the reset process becomes an authentication bypass if weakly protected, which is why SSPR must itself be guarded by MFA or multiple verified factors rather than easily-researched security questions. The governance principle is that convenience features around credentials must be held to the same authentication rigor as the login they can override.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An attacker targets an executive by calling the help desk and, later, by abusing a self-service reset that only asked for a birthdate and pet's name - both findable online. They reset the password and log in. The organization hardens SSPR to require an MFA challenge to an enrolled device before any reset, removes knowledge-based questions, and adds alerting on reset events for privileged accounts. The lesson: a reset flow is a side door into authentication and must be defended like the front door.</p></div><h3>Directory integrity and synchronization</h3><p>In hybrid environments, the on-premise directory is synchronized to a cloud IdP, and the fidelity of that synchronization is a security concern. Stale attributes, mis-mapped groups, or a compromised sync account can silently grant excess access across both domains. Directory hygiene - removing stale objects, tightly scoping the sync service account, monitoring for anomalous changes, and protecting the schema - keeps the authoritative identity source trustworthy. Because so many downstream decisions (authentication, group-based authorization, licensing) flow from the directory, an error or compromise there propagates everywhere, which is why the directory ranks among the most tightly governed assets in the enterprise.</p><h3>SCIM and standards-based provisioning</h3><p>As identity spreads across SaaS applications, the mechanics of pushing accounts and attributes between systems have themselves been standardized. <span class='keyterm'>SCIM</span> (System for Cross-domain Identity Management) is the REST/JSON standard that lets an identity provider automatically create, update, and deactivate user accounts in downstream applications - the machinery that makes centralized provisioning and, crucially, prompt <em>deprovisioning</em> actually happen across dozens of cloud services. Where SAML and OIDC handle the runtime authentication event, SCIM handles the lifecycle plumbing that keeps each application's user store in sync with the authoritative source. Without a provisioning standard, every application integration becomes a bespoke script, and the gaps between those scripts are precisely where orphaned accounts survive. The CISSP framing is that authentication federation and account provisioning are complementary but distinct problems: SSO answers \"can this person log in right now,\" while SCIM answers \"does this application still have an account for this person at all, with the right attributes.\" A mature identity governance program pairs federated SSO with SCIM-driven provisioning so that a single change at the authoritative source propagates everywhere automatically.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Standard</th><th>Solves</th><th>When it fires</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SAML / OIDC</td><td>Authentication at login</td><td>Each sign-in event</td></tr><tr><td>SCIM</td><td>Account lifecycle sync</td><td>Create / update / deactivate</td></tr><tr><td>LDAP</td><td>Directory read/write</td><td>Query and modify identity store</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Active Directory logical structure and trust</h3><p>Because Active Directory anchors most enterprise identity, the CISSP should command its structural vocabulary. The smallest security boundary is the <span class='keyterm'>domain</span>, a partition of the directory sharing a policy and a set of domain controllers. Domains that share a contiguous DNS namespace form a <span class='keyterm'>tree</span>, and one or more trees grouped together form a <span class='keyterm'>forest</span> - and the forest, not the domain, is the true security boundary in AD, a point the exam likes to test. Within a domain, <span class='keyterm'>Organizational Units (OUs)</span> are containers used to delegate administration and scope <span class='keyterm'>Group Policy Objects (GPOs)</span> that push configuration and security settings to users and computers. Relationships between domains are governed by <span class='keyterm'>trusts</span>, which may be one-way or two-way and transitive or non-transitive; a misconfigured or overly broad trust can silently extend access across boundaries an organization believed were separate. A CISSP evaluating an AD environment therefore asks not only \"who is a domain admin\" but \"what does the forest trust, and could a compromise in one domain traverse a trust into another.\"</p><table><thead><tr><th>AD construct</th><th>What it is</th><th>Security relevance</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Domain</td><td>Policy + DC partition</td><td>Administrative boundary, not the ultimate one</td></tr><tr><td>Tree</td><td>Domains sharing a namespace</td><td>Inherit transitive trust</td></tr><tr><td>Forest</td><td>One or more trees</td><td>True AD security boundary</td></tr><tr><td>Organizational Unit</td><td>Container for delegation/GPO</td><td>Scopes least-privilege admin and policy</td></tr><tr><td>Trust relationship</td><td>Link between domains</td><td>Can extend access across boundaries</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Remember that in Active Directory the <strong>forest is the security boundary</strong>, not the domain - a compromise of one domain in a forest can often reach the others through transitive trusts, so highly sensitive systems belong in a <em>separate forest</em>, not merely a separate domain or OU. When a scenario needs true isolation between two business units, the correct answer involves a forest boundary (or the modern tiered-administration model), not just a new OU or GPO.</p></div><h3>Securing the directory protocol and its bindings</h3><p>The directory is only as trustworthy as the channel used to query it and the accounts allowed to bind to it. Plain <span class='keyterm'>LDAP</span> transmits queries and, in a simple bind, credentials in cleartext, so an eavesdropper on the path can harvest passwords - which is why production directories mandate <span class='keyterm'>LDAPS</span> (LDAP over TLS) or StartTLS, and why anonymous or unauthenticated binds are disabled. Beyond transport, the service accounts that applications use to read the directory are a recurring weak point: granted broad read (or worse, write) across the whole tree \"to be safe,\" one such account leaking becomes a directory-wide exposure, so each should be scoped to the minimum subtree and attributes it needs. A further hardening layer is <span class='keyterm'>LDAP signing and channel binding</span>, which prevents relay and man-in-the-middle downgrade attacks against the bind. The CISSP lesson generalizes: because so many authentication and authorization decisions flow from directory lookups, protecting the directory's <em>protocol</em> - encryption in transit, authenticated binds, least-privilege query accounts, and integrity protection - is as important as protecting the domain controllers that host the data.</p><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>A frequent error is treating the directory as mundane infrastructure rather than the identity crown jewel; a compromised domain controller equals a compromised enterprise. Another is assuming password vaults eliminate risk - they concentrate it, making master-credential protection paramount. A third is confusing JIT provisioning with mere automation; its security value is the <em>removal</em> of standing access, not just faster granting. A fourth is conflating authentication federation with provisioning - SSO lets a user log in, but only SCIM-style provisioning ensures the downstream account is created and, more importantly, removed. Finally, self-service is often deployed for cost savings without recognizing that a weak reset flow undoes every authentication control upstream of it.</p>"},
  {heading:"Authorization Mechanisms", body:"<p>Once a subject is authenticated, the system must decide what that subject may do - the <span class='keyterm'>authorization</span> function. CISSP expects fluency in the major access-control models (RBAC, ABAC, MAC, DAC, rule-based, risk-based) and the data structures that implement them (the access control matrix, capability tables, and ACLs). Choosing a model is a governance decision about how much central control versus owner discretion the organization needs.</p><h3>The four foundational models</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Discretionary Access Control (DAC)</span> lets the data <em>owner</em> decide who gets access, at their discretion - the model behind file permissions where the file's owner grants read/write to others. It is flexible but hard to govern at scale and vulnerable to owner mistakes and malware acting with the owner's rights. <span class='keyterm'>Mandatory Access Control (MAC)</span> enforces system-wide labels (classifications and clearances) that users cannot override; access is granted only when the subject's clearance dominates the object's label under a lattice model. MAC is used where confidentiality is paramount - military and intelligence systems. <span class='keyterm'>Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)</span> assigns permissions to roles and users to roles, so access follows job function; it is the dominant enterprise model because it scales and simplifies audit and provisioning. <span class='keyterm'>Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)</span> evaluates policies over attributes of the subject, object, action, and environment at request time, enabling fine-grained, context-aware decisions.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Decision basis</th><th>Who decides</th><th>Best fit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>DAC</td><td>Owner's discretion</td><td>The data owner</td><td>File systems, flexible collaboration</td></tr><tr><td>MAC</td><td>System labels vs. clearance</td><td>The system / policy</td><td>Classified, high-confidentiality</td></tr><tr><td>RBAC</td><td>User's role / job function</td><td>Role engineers</td><td>Most enterprises</td></tr><tr><td>ABAC</td><td>Attributes + context</td><td>Policy engine</td><td>Fine-grained, dynamic access</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Rule-based and risk-based access control</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Rule-based access control</span> applies global rules that apply to everyone regardless of identity - a firewall permitting traffic only on certain ports, or a policy allowing logins only during business hours. It is often a component of ABAC (rules over attributes) but is distinct from RBAC's role focus. <span class='keyterm'>Risk-based (adaptive) access control</span> computes a real-time risk score from signals - device posture, location, time, behavioral anomalies, threat intelligence - and adjusts the decision dynamically, perhaps allowing access, demanding step-up MFA, or denying outright. Risk-based control is the engine behind <span class='keyterm'>conditional access</span> and zero-trust policy: the same user is granted or challenged differently depending on the risk of <em>this</em> request. It represents the frontier of authorization, moving from static grants to continuous, context-sensitive evaluation.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Key idea</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Rule-based</td><td>Global rules for all subjects</td><td>Allow logins 9-5 only; port filtering</td></tr><tr><td>Risk-based</td><td>Adaptive score per request</td><td>New device + odd location &rarr; step-up MFA</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Nail the discriminators: <strong>DAC</strong> = owner decides; <strong>MAC</strong> = system labels the user cannot override; <strong>RBAC</strong> = permissions follow roles; <strong>ABAC</strong> = attributes and context; <strong>rule-based</strong> = same global rule for everyone; <strong>risk-based</strong> = adaptive per request. If a question stresses labels/clearances that users cannot change, it is <strong>MAC</strong>. If it stresses \"his manager grants him access,\" it is <strong>DAC</strong>. If access depends on department + device + time, it is <strong>ABAC</strong>.</p></div><h3>Implementing authorization: the access control matrix</h3><p>Conceptually, all these models can be represented by an <span class='keyterm'>access control matrix</span> - a table with subjects as rows, objects as columns, and permissions in each cell. The matrix is a useful abstraction but impractical to store directly because it is enormous and sparse, so it is sliced two ways. A <span class='keyterm'>capability table (capability list)</span> takes a <em>row</em> - it lists, for one subject, every object it may access and how (a subject-centric view, like a ticket the subject carries). An <span class='keyterm'>access control list (ACL)</span> takes a <em>column</em> - it lists, for one object, every subject permitted and their rights (an object-centric view, attached to the resource). Kerberos tickets are a real-world capability; file-system permissions are ACLs.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Structure</th><th>Perspective</th><th>Answers</th><th>Real example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Access control matrix</td><td>Whole map</td><td>All subjects vs. all objects</td><td>Conceptual model</td></tr><tr><td>Capability table</td><td>By subject (row)</td><td>What may THIS subject access?</td><td>Kerberos ticket, token</td></tr><tr><td>ACL</td><td>By object (column)</td><td>Who may access THIS object?</td><td>File/folder permissions</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A hospital needs a doctor to see records only for patients on their own ward, during their shift, from a hospital device. RBAC alone (\"doctor\" role) is too coarse - it would expose every patient. The team layers <strong>ABAC</strong> so the policy engine also checks ward assignment, shift time, and device attributes, and adds a <strong>risk-based</strong> rule that forces step-up MFA if the request comes from an unrecognized network. Coarse role plus fine attributes plus adaptive risk yields exactly the intended least-privilege result.</p></div><h3>Choosing and combining models</h3><p>These models are not mutually exclusive; mature environments combine them. RBAC provides coarse, auditable baseline access by job function, ABAC adds contextual precision, MAC enforces non-negotiable confidentiality where required, and risk-based control adapts to live threat signals. The governance choice hinges on the organization's need for central control versus flexibility, its regulatory environment, and its tolerance for administrative overhead - MAC and ABAC are powerful but heavy to define and maintain, while DAC is easy but drifts. A CISSP recommends the model (or blend) that matches the asset's sensitivity and the organization's operational reality, then ensures the chosen model is implemented with the appropriate data structures and reviewed over time.</p><h3>The XACML reference architecture</h3><p>ABAC's policy-driven approach is formalized in the <span class='keyterm'>XACML</span> (eXtensible Access Control Markup Language) reference architecture, which the CISSP should recognize because it names the moving parts of any modern authorization engine. The <span class='keyterm'>Policy Enforcement Point (PEP)</span> intercepts the access request and enforces the verdict; the <span class='keyterm'>Policy Decision Point (PDP)</span> evaluates the applicable policies and renders permit or deny; the <span class='keyterm'>Policy Information Point (PIP)</span> supplies the attribute values the PDP needs (the subject's department, the resource's classification, the current time); and the <span class='keyterm'>Policy Administration Point (PAP)</span> is where policies are authored and managed. This separation of enforcement from decision from information is what lets an organization change access policy centrally without touching every application, and it is the architectural embodiment of externalized authorization - moving the access logic out of hard-coded application code and into a governed, auditable policy service. Zero-trust and conditional-access platforms are effectively industrial PDPs consuming rich attribute streams.</p><table><thead><tr><th>XACML component</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>PEP (enforcement)</td><td>Intercepts request, enforces the decision</td></tr><tr><td>PDP (decision)</td><td>Evaluates policy, returns permit/deny</td></tr><tr><td>PIP (information)</td><td>Provides attribute values for evaluation</td></tr><tr><td>PAP (administration)</td><td>Where policies are authored and managed</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Tracing a single request through the XACML pipeline</h3><p>To make the PEP/PDP/PIP/PAP abstraction concrete, follow one request through an <span class='keyterm'>ABAC</span> deployment. A clinician clicks to open a patient chart. The application's <span class='keyterm'>PEP</span> intercepts the call and, rather than deciding itself, packages an authorization query - subject = this clinician, action = read, resource = this chart - and sends it to the <span class='keyterm'>PDP</span>. The PDP loads the applicable policy from the <span class='keyterm'>PAP</span> (\"a clinician may read a chart only for a patient on their assigned ward during their scheduled shift from a managed device\") and discovers it needs attribute values to evaluate it. It calls one or more <span class='keyterm'>PIPs</span> to fetch them: the HR system supplies the clinician's ward assignment and shift, an MDM supplies the device's compliance state, and a clock supplies the current time. The PDP evaluates the rule against those attributes and returns permit or deny with optional obligations (\"permit, but log this access and mask the psychiatric notes\"). The PEP enforces the verdict and carries out any obligation. The architectural payoff is that changing the ward-access rule means editing one policy at the PAP - not redeploying every clinical application - which is the entire point of <span class='keyterm'>externalized authorization</span>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Component</th><th>Action in the chart-access example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>PEP</td><td>Intercepts the open-chart request, builds the query</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>PDP</td><td>Loads policy, determines needed attributes</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>PIP</td><td>Supplies ward, shift, device state, time</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>PDP</td><td>Evaluates rule, returns permit/deny + obligations</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>PEP</td><td>Enforces verdict, masks fields, logs access</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>In XACML questions, keep the four roles crisp: the <strong>PEP enforces</strong>, the <strong>PDP decides</strong>, the <strong>PIP informs</strong> (supplies attributes), and the <strong>PAP administers</strong> (where policy is authored). A frequent distractor swaps the PEP and PDP - the point that <em>enforces</em> is not the point that <em>decides</em>. If a scenario praises the ability to change access rules centrally without touching application code, it is describing <strong>externalized authorization</strong> via this PDP/PAP separation.</p></div><p>A final subtlety is that these models describe <em>how</em> a decision is reached, but a real system must also decide <em>where</em> the PEP sits. Enforcing authorization only at the network edge protects nothing once an attacker is inside; enforcing it only in the application misses direct database access; enforcing it only at the data layer misses business-logic rules. Defense in depth therefore argues for authorization checks at multiple layers - a policy-enforcement point at the API gateway, another within the application, and row- or column-level controls at the datastore - so that a bypass at one point is caught at the next. The same logical policy, whether RBAC or ABAC, can be evaluated at each of these enforcement points, which is exactly what externalized authorization makes practical: one governed policy, many enforcement points, no duplicated logic hard-coded into each tier.</p><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>A common confusion is between DAC and RBAC - both feel \"role-like,\" but DAC hinges on individual owner discretion while RBAC centralizes permissions on defined roles. Another is thinking a capability list and an ACL are interchangeable; they are orthogonal slices of the same matrix, one subject-centric and one object-centric, with different revocation properties (revoking one object's access is easy with ACLs, revoking one subject's capabilities is easy with capability lists). Finally, students often treat authorization as static; risk-based and ABAC models make it dynamic, re-evaluated per request as context changes. One more subtlety worth holding onto is that these models describe <em>how</em> a decision is reached, not <em>where</em> it is enforced: the same RBAC or ABAC policy can be enforced at the network edge, in the application, or at the data layer, and defense in depth argues for enforcing authorization at more than one of these points so that a bypass at one layer is caught at another.</p>"},
  {heading:"Identity & Access Provisioning Lifecycle", body:"<p>Identities and their access must be managed across their entire lifespan, from the moment a person joins to the moment they leave. This section covers the full <span class='keyterm'>provisioning lifecycle</span> - provisioning, role definition, access review/recertification, and deprovisioning - and the privilege-escalation risks that accumulate when the lifecycle is neglected. The governing frame is <span class='keyterm'>joiner-mover-leaver (JML)</span>: each transition is a moment where access can go wrong.</p><h3>Provisioning and role definition</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Provisioning</span> is the creation and population of an identity and its entitlements, ideally driven by an authoritative source (the HR system) so that access is granted based on the person's verified role. The cleanest approach provisions against a <span class='keyterm'>role definition</span> - a predefined bundle of the permissions a given job requires - rather than granting rights ad hoc. Getting role definitions right is a discipline called <span class='keyterm'>role engineering</span>: too few coarse roles over-provision everyone, while too many fine roles create an unmanageable <span class='keyterm'>role explosion</span>. Good role design gives each joiner exactly the access their function needs on day one, embodying least privilege at the point of grant and making later audits tractable.</p><table><thead><tr><th>JML stage</th><th>Action</th><th>Risk if mishandled</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Joiner</td><td>Provision from a role template</td><td>Over-provisioning beyond the role</td></tr><tr><td>Mover</td><td>Re-baseline access to the new role</td><td>Privilege creep from additive grants</td></tr><tr><td>Leaver</td><td>Immediate deprovisioning</td><td>Orphaned, exploitable accounts</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The mover problem and privilege creep</h3><p>The most insidious lifecycle failure occurs at the <em>mover</em> stage. When an employee changes roles, the correct action is to <em>re-baseline</em> their access to the new role, removing the old. In practice organizations simply <em>add</em> the new role's access on top of the old, and over a career of transfers a user accumulates a sprawling, unjustified entitlement set - <span class='keyterm'>privilege creep</span> (also called authorization or access creep). Privilege creep is dangerous because it silently violates least privilege, widens the blast radius of a compromised account, and can create toxic combinations that break <span class='keyterm'>separation of duties</span> (the person who can both create a vendor and approve its payments). The antidote is disciplined re-baselining on every move plus recurring access review.</p><h3>Access review and recertification</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Access review</span> (also called <span class='keyterm'>access recertification</span> or attestation) is the recurring control in which managers and data owners re-examine who holds what access and affirm that each grant is still justified, revoking what is not. It is the primary detective/corrective control against privilege creep, orphaned accounts, and misassigned rights, and it is an audit requirement under most compliance regimes (SOX, PCI DSS, ISO 27001). Reviews should be risk-prioritized - privileged and sensitive-data access reviewed more frequently and rigorously than routine access. The output is documented evidence that access was validated, which auditors specifically demand.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p><strong>Access recertification / review</strong> is the recurring control that catches <strong>privilege creep</strong> and <strong>orphaned accounts</strong>. When a scenario describes users who accumulated access over years of role changes, the fix is periodic access review plus re-baselining on transfer. When it describes a departed employee whose account still works, the failure is <strong>deprovisioning</strong>. Regulators want <em>evidence</em> that reviews occurred - the attestation record itself is the control.</p></div><h3>Deprovisioning</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Deprovisioning</span> is the timely removal of access when it is no longer needed - at termination, contract end, or role change. It is arguably the highest-risk stage because a lingering active account belonging to a departed employee (an <span class='keyterm'>orphaned account</span>), or to a terminated contractor with a grievance, is a favored attack vector and a frequent audit finding. Deprovisioning must be prompt and complete, reaching every system the identity touched - directory, applications, VPN, physical badge, and any local or shared credentials. Automated, HR-triggered deprovisioning through an identity-governance platform is far more reliable than manual ticketing, which is why regulators look specifically for evidence of prompt de-provisioning and why federation (one IdP account to disable) is such an operational win.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Lifecycle control</th><th>Prevents</th><th>Best practice</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Role definition</td><td>Ad hoc over-granting</td><td>Provision from engineered roles</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Re-baseline on move</td><td>Privilege creep</td><td>Remove old access, add new</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Access recertification</td><td>Silent accumulation</td><td>Recurring, risk-prioritized review</td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Prompt deprovisioning</td><td>Orphaned accounts</td><td>HR-triggered, automated, complete</td><td></td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>A quarterly access review flags that a systems engineer who transferred from database administration two years ago still holds production DBA rights on top of her new privileges - textbook privilege creep. Worse, the review finds two accounts for contractors whose engagements ended months ago still active on the VPN. The organization revokes the stale DBA access, disables the orphaned contractor accounts, and integrates its identity platform with HR so future departures trigger automatic deprovisioning within an hour of the termination record.</p></div><h3>Privilege escalation risks across the lifecycle</h3><p>The lifecycle exists partly to contain <span class='keyterm'>privilege escalation</span> - the acquisition of rights beyond what one should hold. <em>Horizontal</em> escalation moves to another user's peer-level access; <em>vertical</em> escalation climbs to higher privilege (a standard user gaining admin rights). Lifecycle failures feed escalation directly: over-provisioned roles hand out excess privilege at the door, privilege creep accumulates it silently, and orphaned or shared accounts provide the credentials an attacker escalates through. Separation of duties and least privilege bound the damage, but only if the lifecycle is actually enforced - which is why access governance treats provisioning, review, and deprovisioning as a continuous, audited loop rather than a set-and-forget configuration.</p><h3>Automation, IGA, and micro-certifications</h3><p>Manual, ticket-driven lifecycle management does not scale and leaves the gaps attackers exploit, which is why mature organizations adopt <span class='keyterm'>Identity Governance and Administration (IGA)</span> platforms. IGA ties the identity lifecycle to authoritative sources (chiefly HR), automates joiner-mover-leaver workflows, orchestrates provisioning and deprovisioning across connected systems, and drives the access-review campaigns that produce audit evidence. A key IGA capability is <span class='keyterm'>segregation-of-duties analysis</span> - the platform continuously checks whether any user holds a toxic combination of entitlements (create-vendor plus approve-payment) and flags or blocks it, enforcing at scale a control that humans cannot police by hand. Modern practice is shifting from periodic mass recertification (which reviewers rubber-stamp out of fatigue) toward <span class='keyterm'>micro-certifications</span> - small, event-triggered reviews fired by a role change, an unusual grant, or a risk signal - so attention lands where risk actually is. The governance point is that lifecycle discipline is only as good as its automation and evidence: a policy that says \"deprovision promptly\" means little without a system that provably does it and a record that proves it happened.</p><table><thead><tr><th>IGA capability</th><th>What it enforces</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Automated JML workflows</td><td>Consistent provision/deprovision from HR</td></tr><tr><td>SoD analysis</td><td>Blocks toxic entitlement combinations</td></tr><tr><td>Access campaigns</td><td>Recurring recertification with evidence</td></tr><tr><td>Micro-certification</td><td>Event-triggered, risk-focused review</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Separation of duties and the toxic-combination problem</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Separation of duties (SoD)</span> is the lifecycle's structural defense against fraud and error: no single individual should hold enough access to complete a sensitive transaction end to end. The classic pairing splits <em>authorization</em> from <em>execution</em> - the person who requests a payment cannot also approve it - and from <em>custody</em> and <em>recordkeeping</em>, so that collusion, not a lone actor, would be required to commit and conceal fraud. Where a role genuinely requires both halves, the compensating control is <span class='keyterm'>dual control</span> (two people must act together, as with two keys for a wire release) or heightened monitoring. A related lifecycle discipline is <span class='keyterm'>job rotation</span>, which moves people through positions so that entrenched fraud is exposed when a successor inherits the role, and <span class='keyterm'>mandatory vacation</span>, which forces a period during which someone else performs the duties and any ongoing scheme surfaces. These administrative controls are not access mechanisms themselves but shape how roles are defined and reviewed, and privilege creep is dangerous precisely because it silently reunites duties the organization deliberately separated.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Control</th><th>What it prevents</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Separation of duties</td><td>One person completing a sensitive act</td><td>Requester cannot approve own payment</td></tr><tr><td>Dual control</td><td>Solo action on a critical operation</td><td>Two keys to release a wire</td></tr><tr><td>Job rotation</td><td>Entrenched, concealed fraud</td><td>Rotate treasury staff periodically</td></tr><tr><td>Mandatory vacation</td><td>Ongoing schemes needing daily tending</td><td>Force one-week absence, cross-cover duties</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An SoD analysis run by the IGA platform flags an accounts-payable clerk who, after two internal transfers, can now both <em>create</em> a new vendor and <em>approve</em> payments to it - a textbook toxic combination assembled by privilege creep. No single grant looked wrong at the time; the danger emerged only from the accumulation. The remediation strips the redundant entitlement, re-baselines the clerk to the current role, and configures the platform to <em>block</em> the combination going forward so no future accumulation can recreate it. The lesson: separation of duties must be enforced continuously across the lifecycle, not asserted once at hire.</p></div><h3>Non-human identities and their lifecycle</h3><p>The provisioning lifecycle is usually taught in terms of human joiners and leavers, but the fastest-growing identity population is <span class='keyterm'>non-human identities</span> - service accounts, application identities, API keys, tokens, certificates, containers, and workload identities. These carry their own joiner-mover-leaver problem that is easy to neglect precisely because there is no HR event to trigger it. A microservice is \"hired\" when it is deployed and issued a credential, it \"moves\" when its permissions change with a new feature, and it should be \"terminated\" when the service is decommissioned - yet decommissioned services routinely leave behind live credentials that never get revoked, becoming orphaned machine accounts with standing access and no owner watching them. Best practice assigns every non-human identity a human or team <span class='keyterm'>owner</span> accountable for its lifecycle, provisions it from an authoritative catalog, scopes it to least privilege, rotates its secrets automatically through a secrets manager, and deprovisions it when the workload retires. Because machine identities now vastly outnumber human ones and frequently hold powerful, unrotated access, governing their full lifecycle is a first-class IAM concern, not an afterthought - and the same review, recertification, and prompt-deprovisioning disciplines apply.</p><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>A widespread error is treating provisioning as the whole story while neglecting deprovisioning, yet the leaver stage is where the gravest, most common failures occur. Another is assuming a one-time least-privilege setup lasts; without recurring recertification, creep is inevitable. A third is adding access on role change instead of re-baselining, which quietly manufactures privilege creep and separation-of-duties violations. Finally, students sometimes view access reviews as bureaucratic overhead, but they are the primary documented evidence auditors require and the main detective control against accumulated, unjustified access.</p>"},
  {heading:"Implementing Authentication Systems", body:"<p>This section descends into the protocols that actually carry authentication across networks - the <span class='keyterm'>OIDC/OAuth flows</span>, the AAA protocols <span class='keyterm'>RADIUS</span>, <span class='keyterm'>TACACS+</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>Diameter</span>, and the internals of <span class='keyterm'>Kerberos</span> (KDC, TGT, and tickets). A CISSP is not expected to configure these but must understand their mechanics well enough to reason about their security properties and attack surfaces.</p><h3>OAuth 2.0 and OIDC flows</h3><p>OAuth 2.0 defines several <span class='keyterm'>grant types (flows)</span> for obtaining tokens, and the exam expects you to know which is appropriate. The <span class='keyterm'>authorization code flow</span> - now with <span class='keyterm'>PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange)</span> - is the recommended flow for web and mobile apps: the client receives a short-lived authorization code via redirect, then exchanges it (with a proof) at the token endpoint for tokens, keeping tokens off the front channel. The <span class='keyterm'>client credentials flow</span> serves machine-to-machine access where no user is present. The legacy <span class='keyterm'>implicit flow</span> and <span class='keyterm'>resource owner password</span> flow are deprecated as insecure. OIDC layers on top, returning a signed <span class='keyterm'>ID token (JWT)</span> alongside the OAuth access token so the client learns <em>who</em> the user is, not just what it may access.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Flow</th><th>Use case</th><th>Security note</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Authorization code + PKCE</td><td>Web / mobile / SPA apps</td><td>Recommended; tokens off front channel</td></tr><tr><td>Client credentials</td><td>Machine-to-machine</td><td>No user; app authenticates itself</td></tr><tr><td>Implicit</td><td>(Legacy SPA)</td><td>Deprecated - token exposed in URL</td></tr><tr><td>Resource owner password</td><td>(Legacy trusted apps)</td><td>Deprecated - app sees the password</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>The AAA protocols: RADIUS, TACACS+, Diameter</h3><p>Network access authentication is carried by dedicated AAA protocols. <span class='keyterm'>RADIUS</span> (Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service) is the ubiquitous standard for network-access authentication (Wi-Fi, VPN, 802.1X); it uses UDP, and critically it encrypts only the <em>password</em> in a request, not the entire packet, and combines authentication and authorization into one step. <span class='keyterm'>TACACS+</span> (Cisco's protocol) uses TCP, encrypts the <em>entire payload</em>, and <em>separates</em> authentication, authorization, and accounting - making it the preferred choice for granular device-administration control (per-command authorization on routers and switches). <span class='keyterm'>Diameter</span> is the modern successor to RADIUS, built for mobile and IMS networks, with reliable transport, better security, and richer capabilities.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Protocol</th><th>Transport</th><th>Encrypts</th><th>AAA separation</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>RADIUS</td><td>UDP</td><td>Password only</td><td>AuthN+AuthZ combined</td><td>Wi-Fi, VPN, 802.1X</td></tr><tr><td>TACACS+</td><td>TCP</td><td>Entire payload</td><td>Fully separated</td><td>Device administration</td></tr><tr><td>Diameter</td><td>TCP/SCTP</td><td>Via TLS/IPsec</td><td>Separated</td><td>Mobile / IMS / 4G-5G</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>The classic distinction: <strong>RADIUS uses UDP and encrypts only the password</strong>; <strong>TACACS+ uses TCP, encrypts the whole payload, and separates AAA</strong>, making it superior for granular device-administration and per-command authorization. If a scenario needs fine-grained control over what admins can run on network devices, the answer is <strong>TACACS+</strong>. <strong>Diameter</strong> is the RADIUS successor for carrier/mobile networks.</p></div><h3>Kerberos internals: KDC, TGT, and tickets</h3><p>Kerberos deserves close study because it underpins Active Directory and appears repeatedly. Its trusted third party is the <span class='keyterm'>Key Distribution Center (KDC)</span>, comprising an <span class='keyterm'>Authentication Server (AS)</span> and a <span class='keyterm'>Ticket-Granting Server (TGS)</span>. The flow: (1) the client authenticates to the AS and receives a <span class='keyterm'>Ticket-Granting Ticket (TGT)</span> encrypted with the KDC's key, plus a session key; (2) to reach a service, the client presents the TGT to the TGS and requests a <span class='keyterm'>service ticket</span>; (3) the TGS issues a service ticket encrypted with the target service's key; (4) the client presents that service ticket to the service, which decrypts it to authenticate the user - all without the password ever crossing the network in reusable form. Tickets are time-stamped, so Kerberos depends on synchronized clocks (a skew tolerance, typically five minutes) to resist replay.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Kerberos component</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>KDC</td><td>Trusted third party (holds AS + TGS)</td></tr><tr><td>Authentication Server (AS)</td><td>Verifies the user, issues the TGT</td></tr><tr><td>Ticket-Granting Server (TGS)</td><td>Issues service tickets from a valid TGT</td></tr><tr><td>TGT</td><td>Proves prior authentication; requests service tickets</td></tr><tr><td>Service ticket</td><td>Grants access to one specific service</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>An attacker who has compromised a workstation extracts a service account's password hash and forges a service ticket - a <strong>Kerberoasting</strong> or, worse, a <strong>Golden Ticket</strong> attack using the KDC's own KRBTGT key to mint arbitrary TGTs. Because the KDC is the trust anchor, its compromise is catastrophic. The defense team responds by rotating the KRBTGT key twice, enforcing strong service-account passwords, monitoring for anomalous ticket requests, and tiering administrative access so the domain controllers are unreachable from ordinary workstations.</p></div><h3>Kerberos strengths and weaknesses</h3><p>Kerberos delivers mutual authentication and true SSO without transmitting reusable credentials, which is a major strength. But its architecture concentrates risk: the KDC is a single point of failure (if it is down, no one authenticates) and a single point of catastrophic compromise (its KRBTGT key can forge Golden Tickets). Its reliance on time synchronization means clock drift breaks authentication, and its ticket model is the target of Kerberoasting, Pass-the-Ticket, and Golden/Silver Ticket attacks. The CISSP framing is that Kerberos is elegant and strong when the KDC and service-account credentials are rigorously protected, but its central trust anchor makes domain-controller and KRBTGT protection an existential priority.</p><h3>Tokens, JWTs, and their validation</h3><p>Modern authentication systems traffic heavily in <span class='keyterm'>tokens</span>, and the CISSP must understand their security properties. A <span class='keyterm'>JSON Web Token (JWT)</span> - the format of OIDC ID tokens and many access tokens - is a base64-encoded, signed structure of three parts: a header naming the algorithm, a payload of <span class='keyterm'>claims</span> (issuer, subject, audience, expiry, scopes), and a signature. Because a JWT is often a <span class='keyterm'>bearer token</span> - whoever holds it can use it - it must be protected in transit and storage, given a short lifetime, and validated rigorously by the recipient: verify the signature, confirm the issuer and audience match expectations, and reject expired tokens. Two classic failures the exam may probe are the <em>alg:none</em> downgrade (a forged token claiming no signature is required) and failing to check the audience, which lets a token minted for one service be replayed against another. <span class='keyterm'>Refresh tokens</span> extend sessions without re-prompting and are therefore especially sensitive, warranting rotation and revocation on suspected compromise. Reference (opaque) tokens, by contrast, carry no data and must be introspected against the issuer, trading a round trip for the ability to revoke instantly.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Token concept</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Key control</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>ID token (JWT)</td><td>Proves who the user is (OIDC)</td><td>Validate signature, issuer, audience, expiry</td></tr><tr><td>Access token</td><td>Grants scoped resource access (OAuth)</td><td>Short lifetime, least scope</td></tr><tr><td>Refresh token</td><td>Obtains new access tokens silently</td><td>Rotate, revoke on compromise</td></tr><tr><td>Bearer token</td><td>Holder may use it, no proof of possession</td><td>TLS-only, short-lived, guarded storage</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Kerberos ticket attacks and their defenses</h3><p>Because the Kerberos ticket model is a rich attack surface, the CISSP should recognize the named attacks and what each abuses. In <span class='keyterm'>Kerberoasting</span>, an attacker with any valid domain account requests service tickets for accounts running services (identified by their Service Principal Names), then cracks the ticket offline because it is encrypted with the service account's password-derived key - weak service-account passwords are the enabling flaw. <span class='keyterm'>Pass-the-Ticket</span> steals a valid TGT or service ticket from a compromised host's memory and replays it, impersonating the user without a password. A <span class='keyterm'>Silver Ticket</span> forges a service ticket using a single service account's key, granting access to that one service; a <span class='keyterm'>Golden Ticket</span> is far worse - forged with the domain's <span class='keyterm'>KRBTGT</span> key it mints arbitrary TGTs for any user with any privileges, effectively owning the domain until the KRBTGT key is rotated twice. Defenses cluster around protecting the trust anchor: long, random service-account passwords (or group-managed service accounts), tiered administration so domain controllers are unreachable from ordinary workstations, prompt KRBTGT rotation, and monitoring for anomalous ticket-request patterns.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Attack</th><th>Abuses</th><th>Impact</th><th>Primary defense</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Kerberoasting</td><td>Weak service-account password in a service ticket</td><td>Offline crack of that account</td><td>Long random passwords / gMSA</td></tr><tr><td>Pass-the-Ticket</td><td>Stolen ticket from host memory</td><td>Impersonation without password</td><td>Credential-guard, tiering, host hygiene</td></tr><tr><td>Silver Ticket</td><td>One service account's key</td><td>Access to a single service</td><td>Rotate service keys, monitor tickets</td></tr><tr><td>Golden Ticket</td><td>The KRBTGT key</td><td>Forge any TGT; own the domain</td><td>Protect DCs, rotate KRBTGT twice</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>Keep the two forged-ticket attacks straight by the key each uses: a <strong>Silver Ticket</strong> forges access to <em>one service</em> using that service account's key, while a <strong>Golden Ticket</strong> uses the domain's <strong>KRBTGT</strong> key to forge <em>any</em> ticket and compromise the whole domain. Any question implying total domain takeover through forged Kerberos tickets is pointing at the Golden Ticket and the KRBTGT key - which is exactly why that key is rotated twice during incident recovery.</p></div><h3>Choosing an authentication protocol for the scenario</h3><p>The exam frequently asks not how a protocol works but which one fits a described need, so internalize the selection logic. For <em>network access</em> - Wi-Fi, VPN, 802.1X switch ports - the answer is <span class='keyterm'>RADIUS</span>, or <span class='keyterm'>Diameter</span> in carrier and mobile contexts. For <em>granular administration of network devices</em>, where you must authorize individual commands on routers and switches and keep accounting separate, the answer is <span class='keyterm'>TACACS+</span> because it separates AAA and encrypts the full payload. For <em>SSO inside a Windows domain</em>, the answer is <span class='keyterm'>Kerberos</span>. For <em>enterprise web SSO across organizations</em>, the answer is <span class='keyterm'>SAML</span>; for <em>modern consumer, mobile, and API-driven SSO</em>, it is <span class='keyterm'>OIDC</span>; and for <em>delegated API authorization without sharing credentials</em>, it is <span class='keyterm'>OAuth 2.0</span>. The discriminating questions are: is a human or a machine authenticating; does trust cross an organizational boundary; is the need authentication (who you are) or delegated authorization (what an app may do); and is the environment a local domain or the open internet. Answering those four in order maps almost every scenario to exactly one protocol, which is precisely the reasoning the CISSP is expected to perform under time pressure.</p><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>Students frequently reverse RADIUS and TACACS+ properties - remember RADIUS/UDP/password-only versus TACACS+/TCP/full-payload/separated-AAA. Another error is thinking OAuth's implicit flow is still acceptable; it is deprecated in favor of authorization-code-plus-PKCE. A third is believing Kerberos never sends anything sensitive - it sends tickets that, if stolen, enable Pass-the-Ticket, so ticket protection matters. A fourth is trusting a JWT because it is signed while forgetting to check its audience and expiry, which is exactly how replayed and forged tokens slip through. Finally, some assume the KDC is just another server; it is <em>the</em> trust anchor whose compromise forges any identity in the domain, which is why it is defended above almost everything else.</p>"},
  {heading:"Accountability, Access Review & Privileged Access Management", body:"<p>The domain closes where accountability is enforced and privilege is contained. This section covers <span class='keyterm'>audit trails</span>, <span class='keyterm'>session monitoring</span>, <span class='keyterm'>Privileged Access Management (PAM)</span>, and <span class='keyterm'>break-glass</span> access. The throughline is that the most dangerous identities - administrators, service accounts, and emergency accounts - demand the strongest, most closely watched controls, because their compromise yields the most damage.</p><h3>Audit trails and accountability</h3><p>Accountability, established conceptually earlier in the domain, is operationalized through the <span class='keyterm'>audit trail</span> - a chronological, tamper-resistant record of who did what, to what, and when. An effective trail captures subject identity, action, object, timestamp, and outcome, and it must be protected from modification by the very users it records, or it fails as evidence. Logs feed a <span class='keyterm'>SIEM (Security Information and Event Management)</span> platform for correlation across systems, enabling an analyst to stitch together an attacker's footprints in the directory, the application, and the network into one timeline. Accountability yields <span class='keyterm'>non-repudiation</span>: with unique identities and protected logs, an actor cannot credibly deny an action - a property regulators and forensic investigators demand.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Audit element</th><th>Captures</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Subject identity</td><td>Who acted</td><td>Accountability, non-repudiation</td></tr><tr><td>Action / event</td><td>What was done</td><td>Reconstruct activity</td></tr><tr><td>Object / resource</td><td>What was touched</td><td>Scope of access or change</td></tr><tr><td>Timestamp + outcome</td><td>When, and success/failure</td><td>Sequencing and anomaly detection</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Protecting the audit trail</h3><p>An audit trail is only trustworthy if it cannot be quietly altered. Mature programs make logs <span class='keyterm'>tamper-evident</span> or <span class='keyterm'>immutable</span> - written to append-only or WORM storage, hash-chained so any edit breaks the sequence, and shipped in real time to a separate logging system that source-system administrators cannot reach. <span class='keyterm'>Separation of duties</span> reinforces this: those who can change data should not control its logs, or the trail loses independence as evidence. This is why privileged users, who could otherwise erase their tracks, are logged to systems outside their own control.</p><h3>Session monitoring</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Session monitoring</span> observes active sessions - especially privileged ones - in real time or via recording, to detect and deter misuse. For administrators, this often means full <span class='keyterm'>session recording</span> (keystroke and screen capture) of privileged sessions, so every command an admin runs on a production server is captured for review. Monitoring supports both deterrence (people behave when watched and logged) and detection (anomalous behavior triggers alerts). Combined with <span class='keyterm'>User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA)</span>, monitoring baselines normal behavior and flags deviations - a service account suddenly reading thousands of records at 3 a.m., or an admin accessing systems far outside their pattern.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>The audit trail is only credible if privileged users cannot alter it. Expect the correct answer to involve <strong>separation of duties</strong> (log admins are not system admins) and <strong>immutable / centralized logging</strong> (logs shipped off-box to a SIEM the source admins cannot edit). For privileged activity, <strong>session recording</strong> plus <strong>UEBA</strong> anomaly detection is the strong-control combination the exam favors.</p></div><h3>Privileged Access Management (PAM)</h3><p>Privileged accounts - domain admins, root, service accounts - are the highest-value targets because they can bypass controls and reach everything. <span class='keyterm'>Privileged Access Management (PAM)</span> is the discipline and tooling that specifically governs them. Core PAM capabilities include a <span class='keyterm'>privileged credential vault</span> that stores and rotates admin passwords so no human knows a static credential; <span class='keyterm'>credential check-out</span> and automatic rotation after use; <span class='keyterm'>session brokering and recording</span> so admins connect <em>through</em> the PAM proxy rather than directly; <span class='keyterm'>just-in-time elevation</span> granting admin rights only for an approved window (zero standing privilege); and least-privilege enforcement that removes always-on local admin rights. PAM is where least privilege, JIT provisioning, vaulting, and session monitoring converge on the accounts that matter most.</p><table><thead><tr><th>PAM capability</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Credential vaulting + rotation</td><td>No static, human-known admin passwords</td></tr><tr><td>Session brokering + recording</td><td>All privileged access proxied and captured</td></tr><tr><td>Just-in-time elevation</td><td>Admin rights only for an approved window</td></tr><tr><td>Least-privilege enforcement</td><td>Remove standing local-admin rights</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Break-glass access</h3><p>Even with PAM, emergencies arise where normal access paths fail - the PAM system itself is down, or a critical outage demands immediate action. <span class='keyterm'>Break-glass</span> (emergency) access provides a pre-approved, tightly controlled path to elevated access for exactly these cases. A break-glass account is highly privileged, normally locked away with its credentials in a sealed vault, used only under documented emergency procedures, and - critically - its every use triggers immediate alerting, heavy logging, and a mandatory post-use review and password rotation. The tension is deliberate: break-glass must be available enough to save the day but controlled enough that it is never a routine bypass. Its use should be rare, always noticed, and always reviewed.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div><p>During a major outage, on-call staff cannot reach systems because the PAM broker is also down. They invoke a <strong>break-glass</strong> account whose credentials were sealed in an offline vault. The moment it is used, the SOC receives an alert, the session is recorded, and the incident ticket references the emergency procedure. After service is restored, the account's password is rotated, the session recording is reviewed to confirm only necessary actions were taken, and the event is documented for audit - preserving accountability even during a crisis.</p></div><h3>Bringing the domain together</h3><p>Accountability, review, and PAM are the enforcement backstop for everything earlier in Domain 5. Strong authentication and authorization decide access; audit trails and monitoring prove what was actually done; access reviews catch drift; and PAM plus break-glass contain and watch the most dangerous privileges. A mature IAM program treats these as a closed governance loop - grant least privilege, log everything immutably, monitor and review continuously, and hold every actor accountable - so that when (not if) a control fails, the organization detects it, attributes it, and responds. That assume-breach, verify-continuously posture is exactly the manager-level altitude the CISSP demands.</p><h3>The privileged-access threat hierarchy</h3><p>Not all accounts carry equal risk, and PAM exists because a small population of identities can inflict outsized damage. The CISSP should rank them. <span class='keyterm'>Service and machine accounts</span> are numerous, often over-privileged, frequently have non-expiring static passwords embedded in scripts, and rarely get rotated - making them a favorite persistence mechanism. <span class='keyterm'>Local administrator accounts</span> on endpoints, if they share a password across machines, let an attacker move laterally by <span class='keyterm'>pass-the-hash</span> from one compromised host to thousands. <span class='keyterm'>Domain and enterprise administrators</span> can alter the directory itself and reach every system, so their compromise is near-total. At the apex sits the <span class='keyterm'>KRBTGT</span> and the domain controllers, whose keys can forge any identity. PAM applies escalating control as you climb this hierarchy: vaulting and rotation for service accounts, unique per-host local-admin passwords (as with a solution like LAPS), just-in-time elevation and session recording for domain admins, and near-inviolable, tiered isolation for the trust anchor. The governing idea is that control strength should scale with the blast radius of the identity.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Privileged identity</th><th>Why it is dangerous</th><th>Targeted PAM control</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Service / machine account</td><td>Static secrets, over-privileged, unrotated</td><td>Vaulting + automatic rotation, least scope</td></tr><tr><td>Local admin (shared password)</td><td>Enables lateral movement / pass-the-hash</td><td>Unique per-host passwords (LAPS-style)</td></tr><tr><td>Domain / enterprise admin</td><td>Reaches every system in the domain</td><td>JIT elevation, session recording, tiering</td></tr><tr><td>KRBTGT / domain controller</td><td>Can forge any identity (Golden Ticket)</td><td>Tiered isolation, tight monitoring, key rotation</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Zero standing privilege and just-in-time elevation</h3><p>The modern endpoint of PAM thinking is <span class='keyterm'>zero standing privilege (ZSP)</span> - the principle that no account should carry administrative rights at rest, because a dormant privileged account is a dormant liability an attacker can seize. Instead, elevation is granted <span class='keyterm'>just-in-time</span>: an administrator requests rights for a specific task, an approval (automated by policy or human) is recorded, the rights are granted for a bounded window, and they are automatically revoked when the window closes. This collapses the attack surface from \"always privileged\" to \"privileged only during an approved, logged, time-boxed activity,\" and it produces a clean audit record of exactly who elevated, when, why, and for how long. ZSP applied to time is the temporal complement of least privilege applied to scope: least privilege minimizes <em>what</em> access you hold, ZSP minimizes <em>how long</em> you hold it. Combined with session brokering and recording, it means even a compromised administrator credential is useless outside an active, approved, watched window.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div><p>When a scenario worries about standing administrative rights that an attacker could seize at any time, the strongest answer is <strong>just-in-time elevation with zero standing privilege</strong> - grant admin rights only for an approved, time-boxed window and revoke automatically. Pair it with <strong>session recording</strong> and a <strong>credential vault</strong> that rotates the password after each use, so a stolen credential is worthless outside the approved window and every privileged action is captured for review.</p></div><h3>Log integrity, retention, and the SIEM pipeline</h3><p>An audit trail is evidence only if it survives intact from the moment of the event to the moment of review, so the CISSP must reason about the whole logging pipeline. At the source, timestamps must be synchronized (via NTP) across systems, or correlating an attacker's movements across the directory, application, and network becomes impossible. In transit, logs should be shipped in near real time over an encrypted channel to a <span class='keyterm'>SIEM</span> or dedicated log store the source-system administrators cannot reach, so a privileged user cannot erase their tracks locally before the record leaves the box. At rest, retention must satisfy both operational needs and legal or regulatory mandates - some regimes require a year or more - and the store should be append-only or WORM with hash-chaining so tampering is detectable. Finally, logging must be tuned: too little and the decisive event is never captured; too much and the signal drowns in noise, defeating detection. A mature program also protects the logs' <em>confidentiality</em>, since audit trails themselves often contain sensitive data. The exam-level point is that accountability is a pipeline property, not a single setting - synchronized, protected, retained, and analyzable end to end - and a break anywhere in that chain nullifies the non-repudiation the whole access-control edifice depends on.</p><h3>Common misconceptions</h3><p>A common error is treating logging as sufficient without protecting the logs - an audit trail an admin can edit is no evidence at all. Another is viewing PAM as merely a password vault; its full value is vaulting <em>plus</em> session control, JIT elevation, and monitoring together. A third is provisioning break-glass without alerting and review, which turns an emergency safeguard into an unmonitored backdoor. Finally, students sometimes see accountability as a detective afterthought, but it is also a powerful deterrent and the ultimate source of non-repudiation that makes the entire access-control edifice defensible.</p>"}
);
